WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.760 --> 00:00:09.230
- Welcome back.

00:00:09.230 --> 00:00:11.660
This is the third panel.

00:00:11.660 --> 00:00:15.640
I'm Eve Blau, the moderator
of the third panel.

00:00:15.640 --> 00:00:20.350
And this panel is about the
planned and the unplanned.

00:00:20.350 --> 00:00:24.010
So the concern of
this panel is with

00:00:24.010 --> 00:00:26.710
the complex and
intertwined relationship

00:00:26.710 --> 00:00:30.010
between planned and
unplanned processes

00:00:30.010 --> 00:00:32.500
of urban environments--

00:00:32.500 --> 00:00:34.570
in urban environments, actually.

00:00:34.570 --> 00:00:36.190
And the central
question that will

00:00:36.190 --> 00:00:38.590
be addressed by the panelists--

00:00:38.590 --> 00:00:41.320
from different
disciplinary perspectives,

00:00:41.320 --> 00:00:45.130
from different geographies
and professional practices--

00:00:45.130 --> 00:00:47.950
is basically, what
is that relationship,

00:00:47.950 --> 00:00:50.730
and what should it be?

00:00:50.730 --> 00:00:54.060
Now I want to say a few
words just about the topic,

00:00:54.060 --> 00:00:57.540
and frame the
session a little bit.

00:00:57.540 --> 00:00:59.940
It's very often the
case, as we all know,

00:00:59.940 --> 00:01:03.780
that official city plans are
not realized in their proposed

00:01:03.780 --> 00:01:05.280
forms.

00:01:05.280 --> 00:01:10.170
Plans are, by definition,
projective and propositional.

00:01:10.170 --> 00:01:13.790
They tend to be
aspirational, no matter

00:01:13.790 --> 00:01:16.350
their claims to pragmatism.

00:01:16.350 --> 00:01:20.400
And they are always political
and always contested,

00:01:20.400 --> 00:01:24.070
as we saw in the last panel.

00:01:24.070 --> 00:01:26.680
In order to be realized,
therefore, they

00:01:26.680 --> 00:01:30.400
require some buy in
from stakeholders.

00:01:30.400 --> 00:01:35.180
But they also have to adapt
to realities on the ground,

00:01:35.180 --> 00:01:39.040
including informal practices
and patterns of human behavior

00:01:39.040 --> 00:01:42.820
that are deeply embedded in
the social and built fabric

00:01:42.820 --> 00:01:44.980
of urban environments.

00:01:44.980 --> 00:01:48.370
As a result, plan
change inevitably

00:01:48.370 --> 00:01:52.130
produces unanticipated outcomes.

00:01:52.130 --> 00:01:54.970
So what is the relationship
between the planned

00:01:54.970 --> 00:01:56.920
and the unplanned?

00:01:56.920 --> 00:02:00.610
In the early 20th century, when
planning, or town planning,

00:02:00.610 --> 00:02:03.040
as it was called
at the time, first

00:02:03.040 --> 00:02:06.190
became a professional practice
and administrative function

00:02:06.190 --> 00:02:11.990
of government in Europe
and the US in particular,

00:02:11.990 --> 00:02:15.070
the purpose of planning was
to control urban development

00:02:15.070 --> 00:02:17.950
in the interests
of the common good,

00:02:17.950 --> 00:02:20.700
by imposing a modest
amount of order,

00:02:20.700 --> 00:02:25.480
and providing infrastructural
support to direct and encourage

00:02:25.480 --> 00:02:28.750
private and usually
speculative development

00:02:28.750 --> 00:02:31.990
of the urban
terrain, and to do so

00:02:31.990 --> 00:02:34.900
without challenging
the bourgeois sanctity

00:02:34.900 --> 00:02:37.150
of private property.

00:02:37.150 --> 00:02:41.050
It was, planning,
and remains a system

00:02:41.050 --> 00:02:43.000
that has always left
considerable wiggle

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:47.200
room for unregulated,
unplanned interventions.

00:02:47.200 --> 00:02:50.410
In fact, I would say that
even the most rigidly

00:02:50.410 --> 00:02:54.790
prescriptive modernist plans,
with their rationalized grids,

00:02:54.790 --> 00:02:57.730
their rigorously
zoned land uses,

00:02:57.730 --> 00:03:02.890
and robust infrastructures, seem
to not only enable, but also

00:03:02.890 --> 00:03:06.160
to accommodate
comfortably a great deal

00:03:06.160 --> 00:03:10.630
of informal and unplanned
extralegal intervention

00:03:10.630 --> 00:03:12.630
and activity.

00:03:12.630 --> 00:03:16.010
In other words, the relationship
between planned and unplanned

00:03:16.010 --> 00:03:21.140
urban processes is neither
dichotomous nor oppositional.

00:03:21.140 --> 00:03:23.240
Instead, it is one
of entanglement

00:03:23.240 --> 00:03:25.370
and interdependency.

00:03:25.370 --> 00:03:27.950
It is even symbiotic.

00:03:27.950 --> 00:03:30.260
Now in recent years,
and this is what

00:03:30.260 --> 00:03:31.970
we will be looking
at in this panel,

00:03:31.970 --> 00:03:36.020
that relationship has begun
to morph in ways that we

00:03:36.020 --> 00:03:39.480
don't yet fully understand.

00:03:39.480 --> 00:03:41.820
The effects of
economic liberalization

00:03:41.820 --> 00:03:46.830
and globalization and
new patterns of migration

00:03:46.830 --> 00:03:50.250
are seriously challenging
normative planning methods

00:03:50.250 --> 00:03:54.480
and destablizing the processes
by which they operate.

00:03:54.480 --> 00:03:57.420
In many parts of the
world, as we'll see,

00:03:57.420 --> 00:03:59.670
urban processes
are predominantly

00:03:59.670 --> 00:04:02.670
informal and unplanned.

00:04:02.670 --> 00:04:05.670
And in general, I would say,
in both the global South

00:04:05.670 --> 00:04:08.160
and the global
North, one thing that

00:04:08.160 --> 00:04:10.770
does seem clear that
is happening now

00:04:10.770 --> 00:04:12.990
is that new actors
are determining

00:04:12.990 --> 00:04:16.470
the economic and spatial
organization of cities.

00:04:16.470 --> 00:04:20.160
In particular,
multinational corporations

00:04:20.160 --> 00:04:22.710
are assuming roles that
were previously played

00:04:22.710 --> 00:04:25.350
by state and local governments.

00:04:25.350 --> 00:04:27.390
Together with
investment banks, they

00:04:27.390 --> 00:04:30.810
are financing urban
development around the world.

00:04:30.810 --> 00:04:34.230
In the process, planning
is taking a backseat

00:04:34.230 --> 00:04:36.360
to private development.

00:04:36.360 --> 00:04:38.490
One could call this
the informality

00:04:38.490 --> 00:04:42.750
of the powerful, as opposed
to the informal practices

00:04:42.750 --> 00:04:46.900
of subsistence and
survival of the powerless.

00:04:46.900 --> 00:04:50.200
As a result, the ways in which
cities are being organized,

00:04:50.200 --> 00:04:53.860
managed, and built and
the political processes

00:04:53.860 --> 00:04:57.560
by which their long term
social agendas are set

00:04:57.560 --> 00:05:00.720
are being radically disrupted.

00:05:00.720 --> 00:05:03.660
These conditions give rise
to a series of questions that

00:05:03.660 --> 00:05:05.850
are the subject of this panel.

00:05:05.850 --> 00:05:09.300
They include-- what are the
planned and unplanned dynamics

00:05:09.300 --> 00:05:11.040
in cities today?

00:05:11.040 --> 00:05:13.350
How do they structure
life and opportunities

00:05:13.350 --> 00:05:15.330
for urban dwellers?

00:05:15.330 --> 00:05:18.210
How can we act on
that knowledge?

00:05:18.210 --> 00:05:21.800
And in particular, how can we
begin to think projectively

00:05:21.800 --> 00:05:25.320
about restructuring that
relationship in ways that

00:05:25.320 --> 00:05:29.370
might give increased agency
and opportunity to the less

00:05:29.370 --> 00:05:33.270
powerful members of society?

00:05:33.270 --> 00:05:35.630
Each of our panelists
will speak to these issues

00:05:35.630 --> 00:05:37.850
from their own
disciplinary perspectives

00:05:37.850 --> 00:05:39.710
and will draw on
their own practices

00:05:39.710 --> 00:05:44.070
in a range of different urban
and geographical contexts.

00:05:44.070 --> 00:05:47.590
The first speaker, our first
speaker is Edgar Pieterse.

00:05:47.590 --> 00:05:50.170
Edgar Pieterse is an
urban scholar and writer

00:05:50.170 --> 00:05:53.410
who holds the South African
Research chair in Urban Policy

00:05:53.410 --> 00:05:56.560
at the University of
Cape Town in South Africa

00:05:56.560 --> 00:05:59.650
and is the director of the
African Center for Cities.

00:05:59.650 --> 00:06:03.070
His research is rooted
in sub-Saharan Africa

00:06:03.070 --> 00:06:06.160
and focuses on urban
development, politics,

00:06:06.160 --> 00:06:09.640
everyday culture, public's
responsive design,

00:06:09.640 --> 00:06:11.890
and adaptive governance systems.

00:06:11.890 --> 00:06:14.920
These concerns in
sub-Saharan Africa

00:06:14.920 --> 00:06:17.790
will be the focus
of his talk today.

00:06:17.790 --> 00:06:22.380
Ana Elvira Velez is an
architect based in Medellin,

00:06:22.380 --> 00:06:27.510
Columbia and is a professor
of Urban and Environmental

00:06:27.510 --> 00:06:37.000
Processes at [INAUDIBLE]
Universidad [INAUDIBLE] ah--

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:39.220
Columbia.

00:06:39.220 --> 00:06:42.060
I tried.

00:06:42.060 --> 00:06:45.130
In Medellin, she
has been involved

00:06:45.130 --> 00:06:47.560
in the extraordinary
and much celebrated

00:06:47.560 --> 00:06:50.390
regeneration of the
city, where she has also

00:06:50.390 --> 00:06:53.860
designed collective housing and
public space, about which she

00:06:53.860 --> 00:06:55.930
will talk today.

00:06:55.930 --> 00:06:59.380
And our third speaker
who is in the ether

00:06:59.380 --> 00:07:03.910
is Ricky Burdett, who will be
actually joining us by video,

00:07:03.910 --> 00:07:08.740
I believe, and various
other remote means.

00:07:08.740 --> 00:07:12.640
He unfortunately
had a conflict that

00:07:12.640 --> 00:07:14.380
came up in the very
last minute and was

00:07:14.380 --> 00:07:17.020
unable to be here today.

00:07:17.020 --> 00:07:21.850
Ricky Burdett is a professor
of Urban Studies at the London

00:07:21.850 --> 00:07:23.800
School of Economics,
where he directs

00:07:23.800 --> 00:07:28.990
the LSE Cities and the
Urban Age Program in London.

00:07:28.990 --> 00:07:31.150
In addition to teaching
and publishing,

00:07:31.150 --> 00:07:35.110
he's involved in regeneration
projects across Europe,

00:07:35.110 --> 00:07:38.290
and he was chief adviser on
architecture and urbanism

00:07:38.290 --> 00:07:45.130
for the London 2012 Olympics
and architectural adviser

00:07:45.130 --> 00:07:49.600
to the Mayor of London, who was
Ken Livingston at that time.

00:07:49.600 --> 00:07:53.020
And his presentation
today will focus on London

00:07:53.020 --> 00:07:56.170
and will draw on
that experience.

00:07:56.170 --> 00:08:00.220
So please join me in
welcoming the panelists

00:08:00.220 --> 00:08:02.490
and our first speaker,
Edgar Pieterse.

