00:09:37.480 --> 00:09:41.740
But in some ways, these trends
and patterns are so stark,

00:09:41.740 --> 00:09:44.950
we have to continuously
revisit and re-inhabit

00:09:44.950 --> 00:09:48.340
these trends to really
remind ourselves

00:09:48.340 --> 00:09:50.800
that the informal
is in fact the norm,

00:09:50.800 --> 00:09:54.790
and what we regard as modern
urbanization is something

00:09:54.790 --> 00:09:57.430
of a distant mirage
for most urban dwellers

00:09:57.430 --> 00:09:59.230
across the continent.

00:09:59.230 --> 00:10:03.190
I'll try and point
to what's at stake

00:10:03.190 --> 00:10:07.060
in the question of the panel
by very briefly showing you

00:10:07.060 --> 00:10:11.260
images of two cities, Cape
Town and Accra in Ghana.

00:10:11.260 --> 00:10:15.580
And then conclude my talk with
responding to the provocation

00:10:15.580 --> 00:10:18.950
that Eve has put forward around
can we think propositionally

00:10:18.950 --> 00:10:21.550
and what form might
that take, and how

00:10:21.550 --> 00:10:24.850
do we re-imagine what
planning could become,

00:10:24.850 --> 00:10:25.960
if we should do so.

00:10:30.030 --> 00:10:32.160
We've heard this
morning in Liz's opening

00:10:32.160 --> 00:10:35.340
remarks of the scale and
the sort of dramatic nature

00:10:35.340 --> 00:10:37.200
of urbanization.

00:10:37.200 --> 00:10:40.920
95% of all urban growth
over the next 35 years

00:10:40.920 --> 00:10:44.130
will take place in
Asia and Africa.

00:10:44.130 --> 00:10:46.440
The important part
for the African story

00:10:46.440 --> 00:10:48.510
is that it's not
just urban growth,

00:10:48.510 --> 00:10:52.230
but rural areas are also
growing because of an incredibly

00:10:52.230 --> 00:10:55.440
fertile demographic
transition that we are still

00:10:55.440 --> 00:10:58.330
caught up in at the moment.

00:10:58.330 --> 00:11:02.190
So in some ways, it is always a
conceit and extremely dangerous

00:11:02.190 --> 00:11:05.550
to speak about Africa as if it
is a geographical entity that

00:11:05.550 --> 00:11:07.110
has coherence.

00:11:07.110 --> 00:11:09.360
This is work that I did
with the African Development

00:11:09.360 --> 00:11:11.820
Bank and the OACD
two years ago, where

00:11:11.820 --> 00:11:14.670
we tried to build a typology
to try and at least begin

00:11:14.670 --> 00:11:19.080
to help us think through
the incredible diversity

00:11:19.080 --> 00:11:20.910
across the continent.

00:11:20.910 --> 00:11:22.650
The detail of this
is not so important.

00:11:22.650 --> 00:11:24.240
The last row shows
you the number

00:11:24.240 --> 00:11:26.550
of countries that fall
into each of the categories

00:11:26.550 --> 00:11:27.990
of the typology.

00:11:27.990 --> 00:11:29.700
But if you look at
the fertility numbers,

00:11:29.700 --> 00:11:33.180
that's really what I want
to draw your attention to.

00:11:33.180 --> 00:11:34.950
Except for the
five countries that

00:11:34.950 --> 00:11:37.520
have got a highly
diversified economy,

00:11:37.520 --> 00:11:39.270
you're still sitting
with a fertility rate

00:11:39.270 --> 00:11:42.570
of about five children
per female in most

00:11:42.570 --> 00:11:45.810
of these geographies, and
of course, very, very low

00:11:45.810 --> 00:11:47.580
incomes per capita.

00:11:47.580 --> 00:11:50.047
The structural element
in the African story,

00:11:50.047 --> 00:11:52.380
and that drives a lot of the
informality we're concerned

00:11:52.380 --> 00:11:55.040
with, is the labor force.

00:11:55.040 --> 00:11:58.230
So in 2010, after a decade
of average GDP growth

00:11:58.230 --> 00:12:02.130
of around 6.5%,
we're still at 63%

00:12:02.130 --> 00:12:04.380
of the labor force caught
up in what the ILO calls

00:12:04.380 --> 00:12:07.110
vulnerable employment.

00:12:07.110 --> 00:12:11.790
This is, oddly enough, it's a
different statistical category

00:12:11.790 --> 00:12:13.470
to the idea of
informal employment.

00:12:13.470 --> 00:12:15.240
I can talk about it
in discussion time.

00:12:15.240 --> 00:12:18.970
But if we shift register
and look at informality,

00:12:18.970 --> 00:12:22.030
you will see that, from the
selection of African cities

00:12:22.030 --> 00:12:24.570
there, which is a gendered
breakdown, that it

00:12:24.570 --> 00:12:29.970
is by far the predominant and
the normal condition for how

00:12:29.970 --> 00:12:30.840
people--

00:12:30.840 --> 00:12:32.850
adult citizens in urban areas--

00:12:32.850 --> 00:12:35.940
access economic life
and livelihoods.

00:12:35.940 --> 00:12:38.370
However, it is not unique
to sub-Saharan Africa.

00:12:38.370 --> 00:12:41.220
It is a condition that, in fact,
is more pronounced in Eastern

00:12:41.220 --> 00:12:43.980
South Asia, as you can see
from the data, or South Asia,

00:12:43.980 --> 00:12:46.140
from the data there,
but also Latin American

00:12:46.140 --> 00:12:49.110
or other geographies
of the global South.

00:12:49.110 --> 00:12:51.720
The point, though, that is
important to keep in mind,

00:12:51.720 --> 00:12:54.480
because urban
living is expensive,

00:12:54.480 --> 00:12:59.250
is that wages are both extremely
low and they're highly erratic.

00:12:59.250 --> 00:13:02.670
So it really complicates
the livelihood strategies

00:13:02.670 --> 00:13:06.330
people need to deploy to
keep a toehold in the city.

00:13:06.330 --> 00:13:08.280
Now what's going on there?

00:13:08.280 --> 00:13:11.280
Despite impressive
GDP growth, we're

00:13:11.280 --> 00:13:14.040
seeing a very bizarre
phenomenon in Africa

00:13:14.040 --> 00:13:17.190
where there's a disconnect
between what we've

00:13:17.190 --> 00:13:21.840
come to expect as a kind
of conventional evolution

00:13:21.840 --> 00:13:23.910
of economic incorporation.

00:13:23.910 --> 00:13:27.090
So there is no industrial
middle being built.

00:13:27.090 --> 00:13:29.820
We're going straight from
agricultural economies

00:13:29.820 --> 00:13:31.900
into services
dominated economies.

00:13:31.900 --> 00:13:35.130
And so if you look at the decade
and a half of high growth,

00:13:35.130 --> 00:13:38.770
it is only in the services
sector in sub-Saharan Africa

00:13:38.770 --> 00:13:40.690
where any employment
creation happened.

00:13:40.690 --> 00:13:43.740
This is a disaster,
because we are

00:13:43.740 --> 00:13:47.310
going to treble the labor
force in the next 35 years,

00:13:47.310 --> 00:13:52.140
from $460 million people in
the labor force to 1.2 billion.

00:13:52.140 --> 00:13:57.510
On the back of a dynamic where
the African region is only 2.5%

00:13:57.510 --> 00:14:00.930
of the global economy, so
it has no bargaining power

00:14:00.930 --> 00:14:05.220
within the rules of the
game of how globalization

00:14:05.220 --> 00:14:07.240
is impacting on the continent.

00:14:07.240 --> 00:14:10.590
So unsurprisingly, living in
formerly and living in slums

00:14:10.590 --> 00:14:14.340
is a pre-dominant condition
for most urban dwellers

00:14:14.340 --> 00:14:19.620
in sub-Saharan Africa,
with significant exceptions

00:14:19.620 --> 00:14:22.440
being South Africa and
the North Africa region.

00:14:22.440 --> 00:14:25.740
So very briefly, if you
look at how people live,

00:14:25.740 --> 00:14:29.130
if you look at how people
work, informality is

00:14:29.130 --> 00:14:31.034
the predominant condition.

00:14:31.034 --> 00:14:33.450
What that means though, from
a planning and a policy point

00:14:33.450 --> 00:14:37.140
of view, is that it translates
into a real fiscal problem,

00:14:37.140 --> 00:14:39.120
because we've got a
very small tax base

00:14:39.120 --> 00:14:41.100
as a result of this condition.

00:14:41.100 --> 00:14:43.200
So if you don't have
a revenue stream,

00:14:43.200 --> 00:14:46.410
where do you amass
the resources to begin

00:14:46.410 --> 00:14:49.620
to respond to the physical
manifestation of this?

00:14:49.620 --> 00:14:51.870
And to give you just
a glimpse of what

00:14:51.870 --> 00:14:55.110
this means in real terms, we
did, for another piece of work

00:14:55.110 --> 00:14:58.890
we did, we tried to work up
what is the per capita spending

00:14:58.890 --> 00:15:02.940
power of public authorities
in various African cities?

00:15:02.940 --> 00:15:05.640
South Africa has a very
devolved fiscal system,

00:15:05.640 --> 00:15:08.440
so you can see it's an
outlier in these comparisons.

00:15:08.440 --> 00:15:11.130
But the next city after
Johannesburg and Cape Town

00:15:11.130 --> 00:15:16.810
is Addis Ababa, and it is
only $91 per capita per annum.

00:15:16.810 --> 00:15:20.260
Right-- per annum-- and
you can see the comparative

00:15:20.260 --> 00:15:22.420
to London or to
Seooul to give you

00:15:22.420 --> 00:15:24.440
a sense of what the
order of magnitudes

00:15:24.440 --> 00:15:28.400
are here in terms of how we
respond to these conditions.

00:15:28.400 --> 00:15:31.690
So in this kind of
context, of course,

00:15:31.690 --> 00:15:34.010
master planning and
land-use control

00:15:34.010 --> 00:15:36.850
take on a distortionary
role, because

00:15:36.850 --> 00:15:39.880
of the predominance of informal
systems of livelihood, economy,

00:15:39.880 --> 00:15:40.870
and settlement.

00:15:40.870 --> 00:15:44.950
And these plans tend to
be incapable of seeing

00:15:44.950 --> 00:15:48.670
that in the way that Dilip
spoke about optics of perception

00:15:48.670 --> 00:15:50.650
and what can be seen earlier.

00:15:50.650 --> 00:15:52.960
Urban regulation is
comprised, of course,

00:15:52.960 --> 00:15:56.440
of multiple systems of
control, rule, and mediation.

00:15:56.440 --> 00:15:59.830
And there is a very, very
dense and almost impenetrable

00:15:59.830 --> 00:16:03.220
logic of coexistence,
symbiosis, and competition.

00:16:03.220 --> 00:16:04.840
It is not kind of--

00:16:04.840 --> 00:16:06.820
the word, the
notion of symbiosis

00:16:06.820 --> 00:16:10.510
might purvey a certain
elegance, but it

00:16:10.510 --> 00:16:14.260
is a rough business
of intense power

00:16:14.260 --> 00:16:15.670
differentials and conflict.

00:16:15.670 --> 00:16:19.960
And it is pretty brutal
in a highly gendered way.

00:16:19.960 --> 00:16:22.720
This, of course, means
that in the larger context

00:16:22.720 --> 00:16:25.660
of political and
governance reform,

00:16:25.660 --> 00:16:28.780
there is this demand
on states to perform

00:16:28.780 --> 00:16:32.650
the ritual of formal
systems of democratic rule,

00:16:32.650 --> 00:16:34.630
whilst, of course,
the real mechanisms

00:16:34.630 --> 00:16:36.860
of running the city, of
running neighborhoods,

00:16:36.860 --> 00:16:38.860
is all about dealmaking.

00:16:38.860 --> 00:16:41.560
And that's really
beginning to understand

00:16:41.560 --> 00:16:45.130
what those practices and
institutional manifestations

00:16:45.130 --> 00:16:48.460
of routine dealmaking
is, that I would argue

00:16:48.460 --> 00:16:50.620
is at the heart of what
this alternative reading

00:16:50.620 --> 00:16:53.650
of planning's
potentialities might be.

00:16:53.650 --> 00:16:58.030
Now last year, we convened
everyone in Quito.

00:16:58.030 --> 00:17:01.720
And of course, everyone arrived,
and no one could get in.

00:17:01.720 --> 00:17:06.130
That's an inside joke for
people who attended the event.

00:17:06.130 --> 00:17:07.960
The logistics wasn't
any where near

00:17:07.960 --> 00:17:10.160
as efficient as Radcliffe's,
and as a result,

00:17:10.160 --> 00:17:12.280
most people spent
half the day queuing

00:17:12.280 --> 00:17:14.470
to get access to the event.

00:17:14.470 --> 00:17:17.020
But this, of course, was
meant to be the moment where

00:17:17.020 --> 00:17:20.950
we were going to confront the
real city as it is emerging

00:17:20.950 --> 00:17:23.290
with all of its complexity
around the world

00:17:23.290 --> 00:17:26.020
and begin to put forward
a proposition about how

00:17:26.020 --> 00:17:26.980
to respond.

00:17:26.980 --> 00:17:30.440
The framework, unfortunately,
was kind of the same old,

00:17:30.440 --> 00:17:31.660
same old.

00:17:31.660 --> 00:17:34.540
The developing story of
basic services and so forth

00:17:34.540 --> 00:17:37.070
was seen to be the
ideal outcomes.

00:17:37.070 --> 00:17:40.180
The levers for change were
these institutional reforms

00:17:40.180 --> 00:17:41.320
at the national level.

00:17:41.320 --> 00:17:43.210
Legislation was required.

00:17:43.210 --> 00:17:45.280
And the means for
delivering this new vision

00:17:45.280 --> 00:17:48.880
was all about territorial
planning and urban design.

00:17:48.880 --> 00:17:50.980
And that design question
I can come back to

00:17:50.980 --> 00:17:51.970
in the discussion time.

00:17:51.970 --> 00:17:57.310
But planning being elevated
as the critical intervention

00:17:57.310 --> 00:18:02.350
point to deliver the urban
century, if you will.

00:18:02.350 --> 00:18:06.880
Now this wasn't particularly
helpful, because what it fails

00:18:06.880 --> 00:18:08.710
to do is to confront this--

00:18:08.710 --> 00:18:12.260
what I call the real city.

00:18:12.260 --> 00:18:15.500
But then, because
it fails to do that,

00:18:15.500 --> 00:18:20.720
it still reduces these
emergent dynamics

00:18:20.720 --> 00:18:25.040
in the city to simply being
an expression of dysfunction.

00:18:25.040 --> 00:18:26.780
And so, of course,
the remedy then

00:18:26.780 --> 00:18:29.660
is political will, sustained
institutional reform,

00:18:29.660 --> 00:18:32.300
credible fiscal policies, and
competent urban management,

00:18:32.300 --> 00:18:32.800
right?

00:18:32.800 --> 00:18:34.790
Who can argue with these things?

00:18:34.790 --> 00:18:38.450
So to kind of maybe reflect
on the challenges of what

00:18:38.450 --> 00:18:40.250
that might mean
in practice, allow

00:18:40.250 --> 00:18:43.970
me to consider two
very quick examples.

00:18:43.970 --> 00:18:49.280
So this is a beautiful public
art in performance in Accra.

00:18:49.280 --> 00:18:52.460
Unfortunately, I can't talk
about that, because as I said,

00:18:52.460 --> 00:18:56.120
I'm rather on this end of
the spectrum this afternoon.

00:18:56.120 --> 00:18:58.620
So what we see across
most African cities

00:18:58.620 --> 00:19:02.522
is this kind of deal
condition of public policy

00:19:02.522 --> 00:19:04.355
that takes on the form
of what I would argue

00:19:04.355 --> 00:19:07.280
is slum neglect as this
picture of [INAUDIBLE] shows,

00:19:07.280 --> 00:19:12.200
in favor of an obsession with
these new enclave elite forms

00:19:12.200 --> 00:19:14.810
of urbanism driven by
private real estate

00:19:14.810 --> 00:19:19.310
capital and developers and
facilitated by public, very

00:19:19.310 --> 00:19:22.230
scarce, public resources.

00:19:22.230 --> 00:19:23.810
The International
New Town Institute

00:19:23.810 --> 00:19:26.190
is mapping this phenomena
across the continent.

00:19:26.190 --> 00:19:28.550
And this is kind of
the latest update

00:19:28.550 --> 00:19:32.630
of the proliferation of these
ambitions and real plans.

00:19:32.630 --> 00:19:36.620
If we look at Accra, classic
example of the challenges

00:19:36.620 --> 00:19:37.760
we face.

00:19:37.760 --> 00:19:39.980
This shows you the
dramatic expansion

00:19:39.980 --> 00:19:42.830
in the footprint of the
city in just 25 years,

00:19:42.830 --> 00:19:45.530
with very, very little
concomitant investment

00:19:45.530 --> 00:19:47.970
in infrastructural capacity.

00:19:47.970 --> 00:19:52.190
So in 1990, when you
saw the footprint

00:19:52.190 --> 00:19:54.980
as the sort of deep
red area there,

00:19:54.980 --> 00:19:57.820
the infrastructural
capacity was merely

00:19:57.820 --> 00:20:00.990
for a third of the
population at that point.

00:20:00.990 --> 00:20:04.130
And there's been very little
additional expansion to keep up

00:20:04.130 --> 00:20:06.770
with the land use encroachment.

00:20:06.770 --> 00:20:11.450
So kind of a whole slew
of infrastructural crisis

00:20:11.450 --> 00:20:12.210
is the norm.

00:20:12.210 --> 00:20:13.450
It's a permanent pattern.

00:20:13.450 --> 00:20:15.410
Only a third of the
city's residents

00:20:15.410 --> 00:20:18.290
have access to water
borne sanitation.

00:20:18.290 --> 00:20:20.840
The three landfill waste
sites were closed down

00:20:20.840 --> 00:20:23.840
in 2015 because of
political conflicts.

00:20:23.840 --> 00:20:25.430
And as a result,
the water system

00:20:25.430 --> 00:20:28.700
got completely contaminated
because of the waste

00:20:28.700 --> 00:20:31.580
systems having-- the waste
having no place to go.

00:20:31.580 --> 00:20:33.350
And what has happened
in the last while

00:20:33.350 --> 00:20:38.030
is a obsession with
delivering this--

00:20:38.030 --> 00:20:40.490
[INAUDIBLE] habitat,
because it is

00:20:40.490 --> 00:20:43.550
consistent with this vision
of anticipatory planning.

00:20:43.550 --> 00:20:46.519
You leave the meso city alone,
and you anticipate where

00:20:46.519 --> 00:20:47.810
all that growth is going to go.

00:20:47.810 --> 00:20:51.550
And you try and get ready so
that you can, in fact, produce

00:20:51.550 --> 00:20:53.000
this alternative urbanism.

00:20:53.000 --> 00:20:57.410
I don't have time to go into why
that is profoundly problematic,

00:20:57.410 --> 00:21:00.530
but it is just to illustrate
that this is a phenomenon we

00:21:00.530 --> 00:21:02.330
see across the continent.

00:21:02.330 --> 00:21:04.220
Quickly, in South
Africa, we have

00:21:04.220 --> 00:21:06.590
had one of the most ambitious
public housing programs

00:21:06.590 --> 00:21:07.960
in the world outside of China.

00:21:07.960 --> 00:21:10.370
It's a similar model to
Chile and to Colombia

00:21:10.370 --> 00:21:13.790
to some extent, free public
housing through 100% subsidy

00:21:13.790 --> 00:21:17.390
that delivers this kind
of modernist stock.

00:21:17.390 --> 00:21:19.460
In some ways celebrated,
very important,

00:21:19.460 --> 00:21:22.460
an example in Cape Town
is an area called Dunoon.

00:21:22.460 --> 00:21:25.640
The dwellings were
delivered in 2000,

00:21:25.640 --> 00:21:31.880
and by 2012, that's what it
looked like in real terms.

00:21:31.880 --> 00:21:34.220
And what that reflected
was a settlement that

00:21:34.220 --> 00:21:37.730
was designed to house
3,000 households,

00:21:37.730 --> 00:21:40.970
15,000 people, in fact,
became a settlement

00:21:40.970 --> 00:21:46.100
within a decade that was
housing 66,000 people through

00:21:46.100 --> 00:21:50.720
in full development,
informal redefinition

00:21:50.720 --> 00:21:52.430
of this modernist vision.

00:21:52.430 --> 00:21:55.580
Now you can just kind of
extrapolate for yourself

00:21:55.580 --> 00:21:58.179
all of the kind of urban
management planning

00:21:58.179 --> 00:21:58.720
and so forth.

00:21:58.720 --> 00:22:00.136
And this is in a
case where you've

00:22:00.136 --> 00:22:03.350
got a $12,000 per
capita country,

00:22:03.350 --> 00:22:06.990
modern infrastructure, high
level of planning capacity,

00:22:06.990 --> 00:22:08.550
et cetera, et
cetera, et cetera--

00:22:08.550 --> 00:22:13.520
and we have no idea how to
respond to this real response

00:22:13.520 --> 00:22:16.130
to these plans, so
to conclude them.

00:22:19.790 --> 00:22:22.760
So firstly, I think we shouldn't
abandon the idea of planning.

00:22:22.760 --> 00:22:24.050
Obviously, it makes no sense.

00:22:24.050 --> 00:22:30.050
But maybe we can reanimate or
recast what we mean by planning

00:22:30.050 --> 00:22:33.710
and think of building a
different set of vocabularies

00:22:33.710 --> 00:22:35.420
and practices, right?

00:22:35.420 --> 00:22:40.430
So the spatial framework
idea remains critical.

00:22:40.430 --> 00:22:43.700
But I think it can
be redeployed to map

00:22:43.700 --> 00:22:47.060
and read the real
city in its fullness,

00:22:47.060 --> 00:22:52.010
formal and informal,
makeshift and organized

00:22:52.010 --> 00:22:53.810
in terms of its economic,
social, cultural,

00:22:53.810 --> 00:22:55.400
and ecological dynamics.

00:22:55.400 --> 00:22:58.520
And we see very few
examples of this kind

00:22:58.520 --> 00:23:02.470
of spatial representation
pretty much, anyway.

00:23:02.470 --> 00:23:04.640
Infrastructure is obviously key.

00:23:04.640 --> 00:23:06.350
But to think of
infrastructure, again--

00:23:06.350 --> 00:23:10.340
and I was so struck by
Dilip's incredibly evocative,

00:23:10.340 --> 00:23:13.590
real representation
of flows and patterns

00:23:13.590 --> 00:23:15.270
that helps us to see
very differently.

00:23:15.270 --> 00:23:21.570
And it's kind of a really
exploded example of what

00:23:21.570 --> 00:23:26.650
I had as a notion in my mind.

00:23:26.650 --> 00:23:30.840
So it was really inspiring
to see that example, for me,

00:23:30.840 --> 00:23:34.920
of what I would regard as this
kind of reading of landscape

00:23:34.920 --> 00:23:37.920
and natural and social
and cultural forces.

00:23:37.920 --> 00:23:41.580
And very, very importantly, and
planners are hopeless at this,

00:23:41.580 --> 00:23:44.490
is building maps
and representations

00:23:44.490 --> 00:23:45.990
of institutional dynamics.

00:23:45.990 --> 00:23:50.160
Because what you have are these
complex, modern, traditional

00:23:50.160 --> 00:23:53.190
gangster, organized
crime, et cetera,

00:23:53.190 --> 00:23:57.690
institutional contaminations
that run these places.

00:23:57.690 --> 00:24:00.700
And we have no way of reading
that or making sense of it.

00:24:00.700 --> 00:24:04.080
And how can we possibly
recalibrate regulation

00:24:04.080 --> 00:24:07.360
if we don't have a language
or way of thinking about that.

00:24:07.360 --> 00:24:10.530
And finally, planning as
a platform for-- and again

00:24:10.530 --> 00:24:13.140
in my work, I'd elaborate
this much further-- this idea

00:24:13.140 --> 00:24:16.080
of Action Networks, which are
not formally institutions,

00:24:16.080 --> 00:24:18.930
but a network of people
committed to a certain idea

00:24:18.930 --> 00:24:20.610
of the adaptive city.

00:24:20.610 --> 00:24:24.240
And in the last minute,
I'll conclude with what

00:24:24.240 --> 00:24:25.590
this proposition adds up to.

00:24:25.590 --> 00:24:29.080
And this is at the core of a
book that will come out later

00:24:29.080 --> 00:24:31.920
in the year and further work
over the next few years.

00:24:31.920 --> 00:24:34.290
But really, I'm very
interested in the idea

00:24:34.290 --> 00:24:36.090
of planning as narrative.

00:24:36.090 --> 00:24:39.090
And if we can kind of
think of the adaptive city

00:24:39.090 --> 00:24:42.900
as an alternative narrative
that allows us to think,

00:24:42.900 --> 00:24:45.810
if you will, these
interdependent

00:24:45.810 --> 00:24:50.040
dynamics in the same
breath, so to speak, so

00:24:50.040 --> 00:24:53.400
that we don't have to be
totally skeptical of technology.

00:24:53.400 --> 00:24:56.220
We can absolutely see
the potential value

00:24:56.220 --> 00:25:00.840
of low tech, labor
intensive enablements that

00:25:00.840 --> 00:25:03.990
can be imagined and
produced off the back

00:25:03.990 --> 00:25:06.450
of new technological
possibilities.

00:25:06.450 --> 00:25:08.400
But at the same
time, there's no way

00:25:08.400 --> 00:25:11.430
that we insist that we
can accept the conceit

00:25:11.430 --> 00:25:13.320
of the smart city idea--

00:25:13.320 --> 00:25:16.350
that you've got to put
in the fiber backbone

00:25:16.350 --> 00:25:18.500
40 kilometers away
from the real city

00:25:18.500 --> 00:25:21.690
so that you can build this
new future utopia that we

00:25:21.690 --> 00:25:24.600
saw some intimations
of this morning.

00:25:24.600 --> 00:25:27.180
So practically, it boils
down to this double move

00:25:27.180 --> 00:25:29.850
that we think about localization
and regional transitions

00:25:29.850 --> 00:25:31.170
at the same time.

00:25:31.170 --> 00:25:33.300
And there is kind of
a font mistranslation

00:25:33.300 --> 00:25:36.960
there, so it's kind of gone
all wobbly in the circles.

00:25:36.960 --> 00:25:38.940
And these regional
transitions is really about

00:25:38.940 --> 00:25:40.950
the big catalytic
ones that allows

00:25:40.950 --> 00:25:43.530
for building fundamentally
qualitatively

00:25:43.530 --> 00:25:45.960
different urban dynamics
and forms and patterns

00:25:45.960 --> 00:25:49.050
and flows and circulations,
energy mobility, ICT.

00:25:49.050 --> 00:25:51.810
But more importantly
institutionally,

00:25:51.810 --> 00:25:55.740
if that is done in a strategic,
intelligent, negotiated way,

00:25:55.740 --> 00:25:58.260
one can begin to address
the fiscal question.

00:25:58.260 --> 00:26:01.320
And in some ways
the most important,

00:26:01.320 --> 00:26:04.560
urgent, politically vital
fiscal planning question

00:26:04.560 --> 00:26:07.980
is a fiscal question, right?

00:26:07.980 --> 00:26:10.710
And of course, none of this
is possible with some kind

00:26:10.710 --> 00:26:14.359
of systematic way of learning
and experimenting and so forth.

00:26:14.359 --> 00:26:15.900
There's another part
of the argument,

00:26:15.900 --> 00:26:18.620
which is about localization,
that I won't get into.

00:26:18.620 --> 00:26:20.390
And then just to conclude--

00:26:20.390 --> 00:26:23.580
in this gesture of what
an alternative approach

00:26:23.580 --> 00:26:28.410
to planning might mean, planning
becomes a narrative device

00:26:28.410 --> 00:26:32.160
that can offer credible
account of the real city.

00:26:32.160 --> 00:26:34.200
Planning then has the
potential to function

00:26:34.200 --> 00:26:37.050
as a deliberative framework,
within which coalitions

00:26:37.050 --> 00:26:40.020
of practice are cohered
to design, test and adapt

00:26:40.020 --> 00:26:42.060
alternative
infrastructure approaches,

00:26:42.060 --> 00:26:44.610
service delivery models and
livelihood strategies that

00:26:44.610 --> 00:26:47.790
can forge a new, adaptive
approach to place-making

00:26:47.790 --> 00:26:49.440
and cityness.

00:26:49.440 --> 00:26:50.219
Thank you.

00:26:50.219 --> 00:27:00.000
[APPLAUSE]

00:27:00.000 --> 00:27:02.400
- Good afternoon.

00:27:02.400 --> 00:27:05.640
I'm very thankful for the
Radcliffe Institute and Liz

00:27:05.640 --> 00:27:08.820
and all her team
to having me here.

00:27:08.820 --> 00:27:11.710
It's been a pleasure to hear
all these thoughts today.

00:27:11.710 --> 00:27:14.610
And I'm almost the last
one, last but not least.

00:27:14.610 --> 00:27:15.550
There's another one.

00:27:15.550 --> 00:27:20.190
So please bear for
the next 15 minutes.

00:27:20.190 --> 00:27:22.950
I've called my presentation
Intermediate Spaces.

00:27:22.950 --> 00:27:26.040
And I will be talking
about housing.

00:27:26.040 --> 00:27:29.040
Because housing is probably
one of the biggest elements

00:27:29.040 --> 00:27:32.550
that build up our
urban cities, and we

00:27:32.550 --> 00:27:37.500
will see this in the
context of Medellin.

00:27:37.500 --> 00:27:39.870
Social housing in
Columbia is planned either

00:27:39.870 --> 00:27:42.330
by the private developer
or the government

00:27:42.330 --> 00:27:44.340
by building mass
produced housings

00:27:44.340 --> 00:27:47.340
on sites outside of
the city or high rise

00:27:47.340 --> 00:27:49.080
buildings in urban areas.

00:27:49.080 --> 00:27:52.650
And course, with no
understanding of context

00:27:52.650 --> 00:27:55.860
or habits of the inhabitants.

00:27:55.860 --> 00:27:57.840
Most of the times,
housing solutions

00:27:57.840 --> 00:28:00.250
seem to be concerned with
the problem of quantity

00:28:00.250 --> 00:28:01.770
and not of quality.

00:28:01.770 --> 00:28:04.810
So let me understand
what does this mean.

00:28:04.810 --> 00:28:07.950
Well, this geometric
element called home,

00:28:07.950 --> 00:28:10.950
it has an inside, where it
should embrace the diversity

00:28:10.950 --> 00:28:12.390
of the human being.

00:28:12.390 --> 00:28:15.240
And towards the outside, it
should preserve the identity

00:28:15.240 --> 00:28:20.340
of the context, proposing new
textures, new places to live

00:28:20.340 --> 00:28:22.690
by understanding three issues.

00:28:22.690 --> 00:28:26.820
The first one, basically,
is landscape textures.

00:28:26.820 --> 00:28:30.270
And we live in a tropical
landscape where mountains are

00:28:30.270 --> 00:28:34.920
huge, vegetation is dense,
water, rain is abundant,

00:28:34.920 --> 00:28:37.500
and sun is strong,
Therefore, it is

00:28:37.500 --> 00:28:42.660
important to live consequently
with our surroundings.

00:28:42.660 --> 00:28:46.020
The second idea is
how do we dwell?

00:28:46.020 --> 00:28:49.020
Popular habits create
architectural elements.

00:28:49.020 --> 00:28:51.450
We need to understand the
different architectural

00:28:51.450 --> 00:28:54.550
elements that identify
a particular community.

00:28:54.550 --> 00:28:58.410
For example, in our Andean
[INAUDIBLE] mountains,

00:28:58.410 --> 00:29:01.860
tropic landscape, life
happens between the inside

00:29:01.860 --> 00:29:02.760
and the outside.

00:29:02.760 --> 00:29:06.630
Somehow, somebody was
telling us this morning.

00:29:06.630 --> 00:29:10.560
I mean, there's no barriers
of inside and outside.

00:29:10.560 --> 00:29:13.230
So this is an important
element in our daily life.

00:29:13.230 --> 00:29:16.440
We have balconies,
terraces, stairways

00:29:16.440 --> 00:29:18.100
where people interact.

00:29:18.100 --> 00:29:20.100
And this is very important.

00:29:20.100 --> 00:29:23.010
And thus this creates
intermediate and collective

00:29:23.010 --> 00:29:24.240
areas.

00:29:24.240 --> 00:29:26.760
So solving a housing problem
cannot be the creation

00:29:26.760 --> 00:29:29.420
of an interior space
to accommodate people.

00:29:29.420 --> 00:29:32.970
What is important is to build
up a sequence of threshold

00:29:32.970 --> 00:29:34.980
between the most
public space, which

00:29:34.980 --> 00:29:40.170
is the streets, the plazas, and
the private space of our homes.

00:29:40.170 --> 00:29:44.040
So the design of these different
housing units cannot be solved

00:29:44.040 --> 00:29:45.900
by designing the unit itself.

00:29:45.900 --> 00:29:49.230
An additional area, which I
called intermediate space,

00:29:49.230 --> 00:29:53.380
is an additional and inseparable
part of the solution.

00:29:53.380 --> 00:29:56.310
We find eaves of roofs,
corridors, balconies, terraces,

00:29:56.310 --> 00:29:59.280
stairs, bridges and
aerial walkways.

00:29:59.280 --> 00:30:01.380
All of these spaces
contribute to the building

00:30:01.380 --> 00:30:03.570
of sustainable
communities and become

00:30:03.570 --> 00:30:05.490
the texture of our landscape.

00:30:05.490 --> 00:30:07.410
In this brief
conversation, I aim

00:30:07.410 --> 00:30:10.080
to explore ways in
which design can

00:30:10.080 --> 00:30:12.900
influence housing
typologies, enabling

00:30:12.900 --> 00:30:15.120
the unplanned to happen.

00:30:15.120 --> 00:30:17.550
These design issues
are capable of hosting

00:30:17.550 --> 00:30:20.430
the rituals of collective
and individual life

00:30:20.430 --> 00:30:24.810
experiences in housing schemes
in the city of Medellin

00:30:24.810 --> 00:30:26.700
and the region of Antioquia.

00:30:26.700 --> 00:30:28.830
So we will see three cases.

00:30:28.830 --> 00:30:31.170
Two of the cases in
the city of Medellin.

00:30:31.170 --> 00:30:34.020
One in the periphery and the
borders and the outskirts,

00:30:34.020 --> 00:30:36.690
one in downtown, and
the other in the region.

00:30:36.690 --> 00:30:39.390
Because region is becoming
a very important issue

00:30:39.390 --> 00:30:42.810
when we talk about
our territory.

00:30:42.810 --> 00:30:46.470
And in the three cases, we
will see different timeline

00:30:46.470 --> 00:30:49.530
regulations, different
actors, and of course,

00:30:49.530 --> 00:30:53.010
how this unplanned
situation of inhabitants

00:30:53.010 --> 00:30:55.830
take into understanding
this new place

00:30:55.830 --> 00:30:58.800
and take an appropriation of it.

00:30:58.800 --> 00:31:01.080
So this is the city of Medellin.

00:31:01.080 --> 00:31:03.870
It is a city of 3 and
1/2 million inhabitants

00:31:03.870 --> 00:31:06.350
where mountains are quite high.

00:31:06.350 --> 00:31:09.810
They rise around 1,000 meters.

00:31:09.810 --> 00:31:12.850
And we will see two
projects in this area.

00:31:12.850 --> 00:31:15.960
The first one is Canaveral.

00:31:15.960 --> 00:31:18.840
This is a project
developed before the turn

00:31:18.840 --> 00:31:20.740
of the century in 1998.

00:31:20.740 --> 00:31:23.160
And it consists of 150 units.

00:31:23.160 --> 00:31:25.470
And it is in the
outskirts of the city,

00:31:25.470 --> 00:31:30.210
because this is where
housing, social housing was

00:31:30.210 --> 00:31:33.210
built due to the land value.

00:31:33.210 --> 00:31:37.590
But the geography becomes
the main tool of design.

00:31:37.590 --> 00:31:40.050
We have very steep slopes.

00:31:40.050 --> 00:31:42.530
And it overlooks the
whole of the city.

00:31:42.530 --> 00:31:49.200
So the question here when
we were designing was,

00:31:49.200 --> 00:31:52.620
how can we design
the idea of a home

00:31:52.620 --> 00:31:54.480
when we had to
develop three houses

00:31:54.480 --> 00:31:57.420
in the same plot of land?

00:31:57.420 --> 00:32:01.470
So this was the answer
we wanted to look for.

00:32:01.470 --> 00:32:04.350
So using the
topography as a tool,

00:32:04.350 --> 00:32:07.890
we designed a plot
of land of six

00:32:07.890 --> 00:32:11.940
by 12, which would contain
three independent houses.

00:32:11.940 --> 00:32:17.040
But each house would have
an access from the walkway.

00:32:17.040 --> 00:32:21.270
So we would have a first
block, a first house, Number A,

00:32:21.270 --> 00:32:25.320
accessing from the
lower block walkway.

00:32:25.320 --> 00:32:31.380
The second house entering from
the upper walkway, and then

00:32:31.380 --> 00:32:33.340
the third one as well.

00:32:33.340 --> 00:32:41.580
So this building of three houses
would build up the whole row

00:32:41.580 --> 00:32:47.100
system of these streets,
which would run along

00:32:47.100 --> 00:32:52.080
the contours of the geography,
allowing that each house would

00:32:52.080 --> 00:32:54.240
have access from the street.

00:32:54.240 --> 00:32:58.020
So this is a concept of house
and not of an apartment.

00:32:58.020 --> 00:33:00.780
So this was very important
when you understand

00:33:00.780 --> 00:33:05.190
what people want when they
become to live together,

00:33:05.190 --> 00:33:07.980
and especially to a
segment of middle class

00:33:07.980 --> 00:33:11.730
or lower class in an area
which is up in the mountains,

00:33:11.730 --> 00:33:12.900
up in the hills.

00:33:12.900 --> 00:33:15.330
And when you understand that
these different elements,

00:33:15.330 --> 00:33:20.220
stairways, patios, and
terraces become incorporated

00:33:20.220 --> 00:33:23.610
as part of the
solution to propose

00:33:23.610 --> 00:33:26.250
those intermediate
thresholds between the inside

00:33:26.250 --> 00:33:29.670
and the outside and
that become areas

00:33:29.670 --> 00:33:34.830
where people in the family
start to inhabit before they

00:33:34.830 --> 00:33:36.220
come to the outside.

00:33:36.220 --> 00:33:40.710
So these are the elements of the
process of planning, which try

00:33:40.710 --> 00:33:44.020
to incorporate the unplanning.

00:33:44.020 --> 00:33:47.040
The second project we're
going to see is in downtown.

00:33:47.040 --> 00:33:50.690
And this is important, because
there is a shift in regulation.

00:33:50.690 --> 00:33:52.530
And it wants that
housing does not

00:33:52.530 --> 00:33:55.620
be in the outskirts of
the city, but inside.

00:33:55.620 --> 00:34:03.690
And this is because the
government lowers taxes

00:34:03.690 --> 00:34:06.360
for the constructors
so that they

00:34:06.360 --> 00:34:09.480
can start to build in downtown.

00:34:09.480 --> 00:34:11.699
So this is the case of La Playa.

00:34:11.699 --> 00:34:14.909
And it is in the downtown area.

00:34:14.909 --> 00:34:19.219
This is a block of
80 by 80 meters.

00:34:19.219 --> 00:34:24.580
And we would have to
develop 254 units.

00:34:24.580 --> 00:34:31.440
And when we got that question of
254 all living in this square,

00:34:31.440 --> 00:34:34.650
we thought how do we
rethink the idea of density,

00:34:34.650 --> 00:34:37.980
and how do we think rethink
the idea of flexibility--

00:34:37.980 --> 00:34:41.350
where we want each person
to have their own apartment

00:34:41.350 --> 00:34:44.760
and it had to be different,
so that this unplanning

00:34:44.760 --> 00:34:47.320
process would start to happen?

00:34:47.320 --> 00:34:50.010
So we designed,
firstly, by the units,

00:34:50.010 --> 00:34:52.290
by the most intimate space.

00:34:52.290 --> 00:34:55.230
So it is a definite element.

00:34:55.230 --> 00:34:59.430
Its a rectangular element
by five by 10.6 meters,

00:34:59.430 --> 00:35:03.000
containing a battery of services
and a single [INAUDIBLE] space,

00:35:03.000 --> 00:35:05.970
with four identical windows
allowing natural light

00:35:05.970 --> 00:35:08.910
and ventilation
for future rooms.

00:35:08.910 --> 00:35:10.980
The walls of the
unit are structural

00:35:10.980 --> 00:35:13.530
and are the finished
appearance of the exterior

00:35:13.530 --> 00:35:15.060
and the interior.

00:35:15.060 --> 00:35:17.250
What we realized,
what was important,

00:35:17.250 --> 00:35:20.940
was that we would give more
area, but less finished.

00:35:20.940 --> 00:35:25.620
Because we know that investment
will happen in the inside,

00:35:25.620 --> 00:35:27.190
and never in the outside.

00:35:27.190 --> 00:35:29.430
So this was very
important in the shift

00:35:29.430 --> 00:35:34.590
of planning that the design
decisions and perfect decisions

00:35:34.590 --> 00:35:37.840
were in the outside, and not
in the inside of the home.

00:35:37.840 --> 00:35:40.380
So this allowed for
an initial investment

00:35:40.380 --> 00:35:44.340
of an unfinished unit, allowing
the highest possible surface

00:35:44.340 --> 00:35:48.270
of 52 square meters
plus a balcony, which

00:35:48.270 --> 00:35:50.040
would be finished
according to the needs

00:35:50.040 --> 00:35:55.420
of the economic possibilities
of the users, unplanned.

00:35:55.420 --> 00:35:58.690
So how do we build
up this complex?

00:35:58.690 --> 00:36:03.670
First, we have a basic unit.

00:36:03.670 --> 00:36:05.800
Four units compose
the service core,

00:36:05.800 --> 00:36:09.580
which has an opening, the main
one and a second one allowing

00:36:09.580 --> 00:36:12.870
a crossing point
on the first floor.

00:36:12.870 --> 00:36:17.550
Four service cores will
build up the first strip,

00:36:17.550 --> 00:36:20.970
the second strip,
the third strip.

00:36:20.970 --> 00:36:24.180
Then you have 12 independent
vertical circulations,

00:36:24.180 --> 00:36:29.360
all going up with a system
of pedestrian walkways.

00:36:29.360 --> 00:36:33.440
And this, all together,
will build up 254 units,

00:36:33.440 --> 00:36:35.720
but in 12 independent buildings.

00:36:35.720 --> 00:36:38.090
And this was very
important as a concept,

00:36:38.090 --> 00:36:41.750
because we could
have planned it up,

00:36:41.750 --> 00:36:43.820
but we decided to
put it the other way.

00:36:43.820 --> 00:36:47.690
And in the horizontal
system, we allowed

00:36:47.690 --> 00:36:49.550
that four different
buildings would

00:36:49.550 --> 00:36:55.710
appear instead of having one, or
three different ones going up.

00:36:55.710 --> 00:36:57.540
So this was very important.

00:36:57.540 --> 00:37:01.610
So our bet was the outer
skin and the relationship

00:37:01.610 --> 00:37:04.970
to the public real and
all invariable elements

00:37:04.970 --> 00:37:07.370
as walkways, common
areas, stairways

00:37:07.370 --> 00:37:10.580
will dignify the intimate
life of inhabitants.

00:37:10.580 --> 00:37:14.260
This basic decision start to
transform the surrounding,

00:37:14.260 --> 00:37:16.850
a new urban park with
the Museum of la Memoria

00:37:16.850 --> 00:37:20.030
was developed later on by the
government in the open areas

00:37:20.030 --> 00:37:21.140
just adjacent to it.

00:37:24.230 --> 00:37:26.510
The opened walkways,
pedestrian walkways

00:37:26.510 --> 00:37:28.940
are the extension of the
activities of the house.

00:37:28.940 --> 00:37:31.490
A neighborhood seems to
arise, where children are

00:37:31.490 --> 00:37:34.190
going to play in the outside.

00:37:34.190 --> 00:37:36.542
And this photograph
really brings me

00:37:36.542 --> 00:37:38.000
the idea of
neighborhood, where you

00:37:38.000 --> 00:37:42.620
see children and people looking
out, being part of the city.

00:37:42.620 --> 00:37:44.690
And this is very
important for us.

00:37:44.690 --> 00:37:50.460
And finally, each unit
inside has a unique family.

00:37:50.460 --> 00:37:52.144
Each one building
their own home,

00:37:52.144 --> 00:37:54.310
allowing for the unplanned
of the process to happen.

00:37:57.974 --> 00:38:03.550
And now we will go to
the state of Antioquia.

00:38:03.550 --> 00:38:06.130
During the years
of 2012 and 2015,

00:38:06.130 --> 00:38:08.440
I was consultant for
VIVA, [INAUDIBLE] Housing

00:38:08.440 --> 00:38:11.920
Corporation, designing rural
and urban social housing

00:38:11.920 --> 00:38:14.920
for the region under
a program which

00:38:14.920 --> 00:38:20.050
is VIP, which means housing
for priority families, which

00:38:20.050 --> 00:38:23.740
was 100% subsidized which
is a program of free housing

00:38:23.740 --> 00:38:25.870
for people.

00:38:25.870 --> 00:38:31.600
And this is a town of Salgar,
southwest of Medellin.

00:38:31.600 --> 00:38:34.930
And it is a very long
and narrow valley

00:38:34.930 --> 00:38:38.260
with a creek in the middle
called the Liboriana.

00:38:38.260 --> 00:38:42.100
And it has a [INAUDIBLE] region,
which has slopes going up

00:38:42.100 --> 00:38:43.630
from both sides.

00:38:43.630 --> 00:38:46.990
And two years ago, due to
heavy and continuous rains,

00:38:46.990 --> 00:38:49.510
as we've been hearing
the last session,

00:38:49.510 --> 00:38:52.670
we had a big overflow
of the Liboriana Creek,

00:38:52.670 --> 00:38:57.820
affecting and destroying
384 homes and 17 bridges.

00:38:57.820 --> 00:39:02.020
In response to this, there
was a reconstruction project

00:39:02.020 --> 00:39:08.580
built between a partnership
of the public, the private,

00:39:08.580 --> 00:39:13.340
and several foundations, as
well with all the community, all

00:39:13.340 --> 00:39:16.780
the families to
build up their homes.

00:39:16.780 --> 00:39:20.200
This process took two
years to take place.

00:39:20.200 --> 00:39:22.600
But what was very important
was the definition

00:39:22.600 --> 00:39:27.640
of where along this very
narrow and long valley

00:39:27.640 --> 00:39:30.070
to find the appropriate sites.

00:39:30.070 --> 00:39:37.840
So two sites were
detected inside of Salgar.

00:39:37.840 --> 00:39:41.770
And the third one, which
is this one to the left,

00:39:41.770 --> 00:39:43.210
is in the rural area.

00:39:43.210 --> 00:39:47.080
But I'll talk about the middle
one, which is La Habana.

00:39:51.730 --> 00:39:53.980
The site had an
irregular geometry,

00:39:53.980 --> 00:39:58.820
has a small plateau,
base of a steep mountain

00:39:58.820 --> 00:40:02.530
on the upper side, and behind
a row of existing one level

00:40:02.530 --> 00:40:07.860
houses, and then next to a
recently built sports facility.

00:40:07.860 --> 00:40:09.910
It then descends
with a steep slope

00:40:09.910 --> 00:40:13.150
towards the main road at
the bottom of the side

00:40:13.150 --> 00:40:15.370
and to the creek
to the far right.

00:40:15.370 --> 00:40:18.310
If the plan was to
build, then, 42 houses,

00:40:18.310 --> 00:40:20.650
the question we
asked ourselves again

00:40:20.650 --> 00:40:24.940
was how can we give the
idea of entering a home

00:40:24.940 --> 00:40:28.210
with this idea of a street?

00:40:28.210 --> 00:40:34.030
And the second thing we
wanted to try to answer

00:40:34.030 --> 00:40:38.800
was what was the appropriate
density for a place where

00:40:38.800 --> 00:40:41.890
we had to reconnect
people who had a tragedy

00:40:41.890 --> 00:40:43.900
and were coming to
a new neighborhood?

00:40:43.900 --> 00:40:47.950
So this was kind of how
do we address this idea.

00:40:47.950 --> 00:40:53.208
And to address this we
designed a project made--

00:40:53.208 --> 00:40:54.590
uh oh-- OK.

00:40:54.590 --> 00:40:57.530
The one before, we saw
three strips of buildings.

00:40:57.530 --> 00:40:59.540
But each strip of
building was designed

00:40:59.540 --> 00:41:01.830
by a unit called the Gallery.

00:41:01.830 --> 00:41:06.050
So if the inside was developed
with the regulations that

00:41:06.050 --> 00:41:10.580
were asked by government, we bet
on proposing a collective area

00:41:10.580 --> 00:41:12.440
which is at the
outside, which was

00:41:12.440 --> 00:41:15.170
a common pedestrian
street or a balcony

00:41:15.170 --> 00:41:18.740
or a porch which would
allow this interaction

00:41:18.740 --> 00:41:22.760
of the old neighborhood with
a new neighborhood to happen.

00:41:22.760 --> 00:41:25.400
So planning would
happen with the families

00:41:25.400 --> 00:41:27.710
to understand how
their belongings would

00:41:27.710 --> 00:41:30.270
come into their homes.

00:41:30.270 --> 00:41:33.380
So that was planned,
that took place.

00:41:33.380 --> 00:41:36.470
But what was important
was the outside,

00:41:36.470 --> 00:41:41.240
because we gave this kind of
porch with a little bench.

00:41:41.240 --> 00:41:46.030
But by allowing this bench,
concrete bench to appear,

00:41:46.030 --> 00:41:50.910
it allowed people to use the
space as they really wanted.

00:41:50.910 --> 00:41:52.100
And identity happened.

00:41:52.100 --> 00:41:53.860
So you see chairs.

00:41:53.860 --> 00:41:56.690
You see vegetation.

00:41:56.690 --> 00:41:59.990
You see afternoon talk.

00:41:59.990 --> 00:42:03.930
You see children playing,
or they are looking after,

00:42:03.930 --> 00:42:09.900
like this was a huge crib,
people observing, looking down.

00:42:09.900 --> 00:42:12.570
And this is our bet.

00:42:12.570 --> 00:42:16.770
I mean, we want to build
up communities where people

00:42:16.770 --> 00:42:18.070
interact with the building.

00:42:18.070 --> 00:42:21.510
So we plan to a certain point,
but then it is important

00:42:21.510 --> 00:42:25.530
that the unplanned, but we
know it's part of the process,

00:42:25.530 --> 00:42:26.910
takes place.

00:42:26.910 --> 00:42:30.660
So these are the buildings
in the situation today,

00:42:30.660 --> 00:42:32.990
looking down into the valley.

00:42:32.990 --> 00:42:35.850
But we consider that
it is from the inside

00:42:35.850 --> 00:42:38.700
that we have to
plan the context.

00:42:38.700 --> 00:42:41.340
I mean, we work both
scales, but it is important

00:42:41.340 --> 00:42:43.740
this relationship from
one side to the other.

00:42:49.080 --> 00:42:53.580
So we have seen three cases of
planned social housing schemes

00:42:53.580 --> 00:42:57.390
where design can influence
housing typologies enabling

00:42:57.390 --> 00:43:01.620
the unplanned to take
place by an appropriation

00:43:01.620 --> 00:43:06.690
of the private space, or
beyond, with local identity

00:43:06.690 --> 00:43:08.953
and with human experiences.

00:43:08.953 --> 00:43:09.939
Thank you.

00:43:09.939 --> 00:43:17.840
