00:43:23.810 --> 00:43:25.010
Good evening to everybody.

00:43:25.010 --> 00:43:27.200
And I hope you can
hear me, and apologies

00:43:27.200 --> 00:43:28.970
for not being with you.

00:43:28.970 --> 00:43:29.780
Can you hear me?

00:43:34.260 --> 00:43:35.700
- Can you hear us?

00:43:35.700 --> 00:43:36.470
- Yes.

00:43:36.470 --> 00:43:36.970
- Good.

00:43:36.970 --> 00:43:39.160
[LAUGHTER]

00:43:39.160 --> 00:43:39.940
- OK.

00:43:39.940 --> 00:43:42.940
So what I want to
do in my time is

00:43:42.940 --> 00:43:47.530
to respond to Eve's very
interesting introduction

00:43:47.530 --> 00:43:51.640
about the status of
planning and also

00:43:51.640 --> 00:43:56.977
pick up on some of the issues
that both Edgar and Ana

00:43:56.977 --> 00:43:58.060
Elvira have talked about--

00:43:58.060 --> 00:44:02.650
Edgar focusing
importantly on the aspect

00:44:02.650 --> 00:44:07.180
of institutional dynamics
and Ana Elvira fundamentally

00:44:07.180 --> 00:44:10.480
talking about
design and quality.

00:44:10.480 --> 00:44:14.950
And what I want to do is talk
about both of these aspects

00:44:14.950 --> 00:44:18.880
and how planning should
and can, and Eve,

00:44:18.880 --> 00:44:22.810
I want to be optimistic here,
actually bring both together.

00:44:22.810 --> 00:44:27.970
And I want to do this through
the examples in London.

00:44:27.970 --> 00:44:28.630
Next slide.

00:44:32.110 --> 00:44:35.590
As Edgar has already
described, it's

00:44:35.590 --> 00:44:39.980
impossible to talk about
one aspect of planning.

00:44:39.980 --> 00:44:43.990
It's also impossible to talk
about one aspect of a city.

00:44:43.990 --> 00:44:48.280
My city, London, is a
city with an average GDP

00:44:48.280 --> 00:44:51.400
of $50,000 a year.

00:44:51.400 --> 00:44:56.140
And we saw from Edgar's
statistics, that $15,000 a year

00:44:56.140 --> 00:44:59.380
are invested in infrastructure.

00:44:59.380 --> 00:45:04.080
It's a city which has 500 banks
and international headquarters.

00:45:04.080 --> 00:45:09.140
But the next slide also shows
another aspect of London.

00:45:09.140 --> 00:45:13.190
It's actually a low density,
nearly bucolic city.

00:45:13.190 --> 00:45:16.340
But if you look very
carefully at the skyline which

00:45:16.340 --> 00:45:19.580
is emerging from this
image, you can feel

00:45:19.580 --> 00:45:23.240
the tensions of that growth.

00:45:23.240 --> 00:45:26.210
And it's exactly
here that planning

00:45:26.210 --> 00:45:29.000
can intervene in a useful way.

00:45:29.000 --> 00:45:31.470
Next.

00:45:31.470 --> 00:45:37.200
But unlike sub-Saharan
Africa, and to a degree

00:45:37.200 --> 00:45:43.800
unlike Medellin, London is an
old, creaky, difficult, mature

00:45:43.800 --> 00:45:45.740
city.

00:45:45.740 --> 00:45:48.620
And if you want
to absorb growth--

00:45:48.620 --> 00:45:51.710
and let's remind
ourselves, those cities

00:45:51.710 --> 00:45:55.340
which need and have
growth are lucky, as

00:45:55.340 --> 00:45:57.200
opposed to the
opposite, of people

00:45:57.200 --> 00:46:01.220
leaving cities and leaving
because they have no jobs--

00:46:01.220 --> 00:46:05.270
if we want to absorb growth
in a city like London,

00:46:05.270 --> 00:46:09.350
we have to absorb
it within existing

00:46:09.350 --> 00:46:13.090
spaces like the one we
see represented here,

00:46:13.090 --> 00:46:14.000
or the next slide.

00:46:16.600 --> 00:46:20.560
I want to talk in fact about
two projects which have filled

00:46:20.560 --> 00:46:23.770
the gaps of these cities.

00:46:23.770 --> 00:46:28.780
And in response to Eve's first
provocation about public sector

00:46:28.780 --> 00:46:31.930
and private sector, I
want to nearly conclude

00:46:31.930 --> 00:46:36.920
right at the beginning that
private development need not

00:46:36.920 --> 00:46:41.120
be negative as long
as it is well-planned.

00:46:41.120 --> 00:46:45.590
And public sector by
definition is not positive

00:46:45.590 --> 00:46:47.510
unless it's well-planned.

00:46:47.510 --> 00:46:52.480
And this is where the adaptive
nature of planning is central.

00:46:52.480 --> 00:46:54.230
And the two examples
I want to give

00:46:54.230 --> 00:46:59.220
are the Olympic neighborhood
in the east of London,

00:46:59.220 --> 00:47:03.350
which is an ongoing
project 100% funded

00:47:03.350 --> 00:47:07.340
by the public sector to
the tune of $15 billion

00:47:07.340 --> 00:47:10.560
over a long period of time.

00:47:10.560 --> 00:47:14.860
And the next, a private
sector development,

00:47:14.860 --> 00:47:17.520
100% private, which
is also ongoing

00:47:17.520 --> 00:47:21.130
in a more central part of
London, which is being built

00:47:21.130 --> 00:47:23.980
by investors and pension funds.

00:47:23.980 --> 00:47:27.640
Where Eve, just to respond
to your provocation,

00:47:27.640 --> 00:47:34.390
I think actually, well-designed,
high quality public spaces

00:47:34.390 --> 00:47:37.750
which are adaptable, whether
it's public or privately funded

00:47:37.750 --> 00:47:40.780
can actually respond to
the needs of the city.

00:47:40.780 --> 00:47:43.650
Next slide.

00:47:43.650 --> 00:47:46.860
If you look at this image
really quite carefully,

00:47:46.860 --> 00:47:51.520
and you zoom in, I know it
may be a bit out of focus,

00:47:51.520 --> 00:47:55.840
you see one of the most livable
cities in the global north.

00:47:55.840 --> 00:47:59.980
It's a part of London, north
London, which actually,

00:47:59.980 --> 00:48:03.700
from where you're sitting and
from where I'm sitting, looks

00:48:03.700 --> 00:48:06.530
and is a mess.

00:48:06.530 --> 00:48:09.960
And I think the provocation
for all of us in this panel,

00:48:09.960 --> 00:48:13.380
is how can you actually
design an infrastructure which

00:48:13.380 --> 00:48:16.150
allows a degree of messiness?

00:48:16.150 --> 00:48:20.190
Eve, you introduced, very
interestingly, the notion

00:48:20.190 --> 00:48:23.890
of wiggle room at the beginning.

00:48:23.890 --> 00:48:26.530
I think we need to
understand, in our planning,

00:48:26.530 --> 00:48:29.980
how to adapt and
allow for wiggle room.

00:48:29.980 --> 00:48:34.930
And I think I concur with
Edgar that maybe the best

00:48:34.930 --> 00:48:39.640
form of planning is not
to anticipate outcomes,

00:48:39.640 --> 00:48:42.100
not to anticipate outcomes.

00:48:42.100 --> 00:48:44.020
And what we're
seeing in this image

00:48:44.020 --> 00:48:46.030
is maybe something
about that, and I'll

00:48:46.030 --> 00:48:48.050
conclude with that in a moment.

00:48:48.050 --> 00:48:50.880
Next slide.

00:48:50.880 --> 00:48:53.600
There are other
ways of planning.

00:48:53.600 --> 00:48:56.300
This is the archetypal
way of planning

00:48:56.300 --> 00:48:58.380
a city from the
19th century, which

00:48:58.380 --> 00:49:01.860
has served this city well.

00:49:01.860 --> 00:49:06.200
Or there's another model, which
is depicted in the next slide,

00:49:06.200 --> 00:49:10.100
of a part of Rome, a central
part of Rome, which to a degree

00:49:10.100 --> 00:49:13.790
had planning, but an enormous
amount of informal growth.

00:49:13.790 --> 00:49:17.940
We could call it that, extremely
beautiful informal growth,

00:49:17.940 --> 00:49:21.860
which has reacted and adapted
to the tissue which is there

00:49:21.860 --> 00:49:25.010
with high level of
quality of public space.

00:49:25.010 --> 00:49:26.710
Next slide.

00:49:26.710 --> 00:49:30.580
London, in this
image, is organic.

00:49:30.580 --> 00:49:31.720
It's messy.

00:49:31.720 --> 00:49:35.930
It's unplanned, and therefore,
it's also extremely fragile,

00:49:35.930 --> 00:49:37.900
maybe an issue we can
come back to at the end.

00:49:37.900 --> 00:49:40.640
Next slide.

00:49:40.640 --> 00:49:43.610
Politics, as Edgar has
told us, is fundamental.

00:49:43.610 --> 00:49:46.760
You just can't talk about
planning without understanding

00:49:46.760 --> 00:49:49.130
the institutional dynamics.

00:49:49.130 --> 00:49:53.240
We happened to have invented,
over the last 16 years,

00:49:53.240 --> 00:49:57.230
the concept of a directly
elected mayor in London.

00:49:57.230 --> 00:49:58.850
This has been instrumental.

00:49:58.850 --> 00:50:00.630
Next slide.

00:50:00.630 --> 00:50:03.900
The reality-- you can't
see what's on this slide--

00:50:03.900 --> 00:50:07.170
is that's actually
how planning works.

00:50:07.170 --> 00:50:10.170
There are many different bodies,
many different institutions.

00:50:10.170 --> 00:50:11.650
And Edgar is absolutely right.

00:50:11.650 --> 00:50:13.950
We need to understand
those first, whose

00:50:13.950 --> 00:50:15.750
voice is being understood?

00:50:15.750 --> 00:50:17.460
But you need a
framework to do that.

00:50:17.460 --> 00:50:17.985
Next slide.

00:50:20.790 --> 00:50:23.130
London happens to be growing.

00:50:23.130 --> 00:50:25.350
It's now just
about nine million,

00:50:25.350 --> 00:50:27.600
and it will be 10
million by 2030.

00:50:27.600 --> 00:50:30.310
Next slide.

00:50:30.310 --> 00:50:34.330
But there is a policy in place
which says that London cannot

00:50:34.330 --> 00:50:37.340
grow outside its boundary.

00:50:37.340 --> 00:50:39.310
That's a very
strong planning act

00:50:39.310 --> 00:50:43.390
from the 1940s, which has
imposed a limit, and therefore

00:50:43.390 --> 00:50:48.160
reduced sprawl, I think one
of the most intelligent forms

00:50:48.160 --> 00:50:50.110
of planning that I know.

00:50:50.110 --> 00:50:53.590
So where do you grow when you
have the need to accommodate

00:50:53.590 --> 00:50:55.030
one more million people?

00:50:55.030 --> 00:50:57.120
Next slide.

00:50:57.120 --> 00:51:01.560
Well, you find the gashes,
the open spaces that you have.

00:51:01.560 --> 00:51:03.380
Next slide.

00:51:03.380 --> 00:51:08.270
And this has meant that London
is slowly but firmly moving

00:51:08.270 --> 00:51:12.260
east, where many of the
ex-industrial spaces are.

00:51:12.260 --> 00:51:14.410
Next.

00:51:14.410 --> 00:51:17.810
And the London plan, we did
not go into this in detail,

00:51:17.810 --> 00:51:21.010
focuses on these two things.

00:51:21.010 --> 00:51:23.110
Keep the city within its limits.

00:51:23.110 --> 00:51:27.910
You need a powerful political
structure to do that.

00:51:27.910 --> 00:51:32.230
But allow and encourage
development along the areas

00:51:32.230 --> 00:51:33.840
that you need to--

00:51:33.840 --> 00:51:40.060
next-- particularly in areas
which have available land,

00:51:40.060 --> 00:51:43.600
like the two examples I'm going
to talk about in the next part

00:51:43.600 --> 00:51:45.950
of my talk-- next--

00:51:45.950 --> 00:51:49.760
the King's Cross development
and the Olympic quarter, both

00:51:49.760 --> 00:51:54.390
located in slightly central
but peripheral areas of London.

00:51:54.390 --> 00:51:56.440
Next.

00:51:56.440 --> 00:51:58.870
To understand London,
and this is responding

00:51:58.870 --> 00:52:03.760
to Edgar's request,
in a good way,

00:52:03.760 --> 00:52:07.130
you need to understand
what the real city is.

00:52:07.130 --> 00:52:10.160
This map shows in red where
the people who are most

00:52:10.160 --> 00:52:15.710
deprived in our city, in this
decade of the 21st century,

00:52:15.710 --> 00:52:16.820
are.

00:52:16.820 --> 00:52:19.490
And then green
are most affluent.

00:52:19.490 --> 00:52:23.900
You can see a split between east
and west and between periphery

00:52:23.900 --> 00:52:25.720
and center.

00:52:25.720 --> 00:52:28.720
Summarizing it very
quickly, it is the east

00:52:28.720 --> 00:52:30.520
that is the most deprived.

00:52:30.520 --> 00:52:34.060
If you did this map in
Paris and perhaps in Boston,

00:52:34.060 --> 00:52:36.550
you would have a completely
different diagram.

00:52:36.550 --> 00:52:38.590
You need to understand
the structure

00:52:38.590 --> 00:52:43.000
within you're working before you
employ mechanisms to solve it.

00:52:43.000 --> 00:52:45.200
Next.

00:52:45.200 --> 00:52:48.290
So our two areas are actually
in some of the most deprived

00:52:48.290 --> 00:52:49.580
parts of the city.

00:52:49.580 --> 00:52:52.340
Next.

00:52:52.340 --> 00:52:57.860
When London, by mistake, won the
Olympics for the 2012 event--

00:52:57.860 --> 00:53:01.840
if you remember, New York
was the strongest candidate--

00:53:01.840 --> 00:53:05.170
the first decision that was
made, let's put it in an area

00:53:05.170 --> 00:53:08.620
where we can do good
things with the $15 billion

00:53:08.620 --> 00:53:11.030
of public money.

00:53:11.030 --> 00:53:14.720
And let's try and not
make it into a ghetto,

00:53:14.720 --> 00:53:17.930
but make it into an
integrated piece of city.

00:53:17.930 --> 00:53:21.440
This is exactly what Ana
Elvira has been talking about.

00:53:21.440 --> 00:53:25.250
How do you, at the scale,
in her case of housing,

00:53:25.250 --> 00:53:28.940
create streets and connections,
so that as the city grows up

00:53:28.940 --> 00:53:31.250
around it or as you
integrate it with it,

00:53:31.250 --> 00:53:35.090
it does not stand alone
as an isolated ghetto?

00:53:35.090 --> 00:53:37.430
Eve, this is the planning
you've been talking

00:53:37.430 --> 00:53:39.230
about which is negative.

00:53:39.230 --> 00:53:41.810
The one that actually
creates what is on the left

00:53:41.810 --> 00:53:43.670
and not what is on the right.

00:53:43.670 --> 00:53:46.250
Next.

00:53:46.250 --> 00:53:48.470
What happened in the
site of the Olympics,

00:53:48.470 --> 00:53:51.040
you can see it there
circled in green,

00:53:51.040 --> 00:53:55.310
is to take a site which was a
railway, disused railway land,

00:53:55.310 --> 00:53:58.070
surrounded by strong
sense of community,

00:53:58.070 --> 00:54:00.440
but literally cut off
from its surroundings.

00:54:00.440 --> 00:54:02.416
Next.

00:54:02.416 --> 00:54:03.540
That's what it looked like.

00:54:03.540 --> 00:54:05.600
Next.

00:54:05.600 --> 00:54:08.420
And that's where my fridge
and everyone else's fridge

00:54:08.420 --> 00:54:11.060
in London was dumped
for many, many years.

00:54:11.060 --> 00:54:13.080
Cities have back spaces.

00:54:13.080 --> 00:54:14.970
How do you foreground
them is the issue.

00:54:14.970 --> 00:54:16.930
Next.

00:54:16.930 --> 00:54:19.870
It's a place surrounded by
strong migrant communities

00:54:19.870 --> 00:54:21.520
from different
parts of the world

00:54:21.520 --> 00:54:23.950
and different
ethnicities, very rich.

00:54:23.950 --> 00:54:26.070
Next.

00:54:26.070 --> 00:54:29.160
And there was a desire
by the government

00:54:29.160 --> 00:54:35.400
to use this policy to try and
effectively redistribute wealth

00:54:35.400 --> 00:54:37.350
through long term planning.

00:54:37.350 --> 00:54:39.000
And time is essential to this.

00:54:39.000 --> 00:54:41.220
Next.

00:54:41.220 --> 00:54:42.630
So this was the vision.

00:54:42.630 --> 00:54:45.080
These are the visions
that we all hate.

00:54:45.080 --> 00:54:48.260
It's an image of a sort
of perfect seamless

00:54:48.260 --> 00:54:50.499
community fixed in time.

00:54:50.499 --> 00:54:52.040
What I want to say
in the few minutes

00:54:52.040 --> 00:54:54.620
that I talk about this
and the next project,

00:54:54.620 --> 00:54:56.540
is how can you try
and actually work

00:54:56.540 --> 00:55:01.580
against the grain of fixity of
the image that you see here?

00:55:01.580 --> 00:55:03.350
Next slide.

00:55:03.350 --> 00:55:07.220
Well, this is an image of fridge
mountain during the Olympics

00:55:07.220 --> 00:55:10.460
itself, a nice park with
a stadium behind it.

00:55:10.460 --> 00:55:12.500
Next.

00:55:12.500 --> 00:55:14.330
But you'll also
remember the slide

00:55:14.330 --> 00:55:16.610
that I showed you that
the site was totally

00:55:16.610 --> 00:55:18.560
isolated from its surrounding.

00:55:18.560 --> 00:55:20.930
It was a railway goods yard.

00:55:20.930 --> 00:55:26.030
So the first chunk, in fact,
roughly a billion dollars

00:55:26.030 --> 00:55:29.840
of the money from
central government

00:55:29.840 --> 00:55:35.420
was used to create 37
bridges, links, connections

00:55:35.420 --> 00:55:39.410
between this empty hole
and the rest of the city.

00:55:39.410 --> 00:55:40.970
In other words,
it's the beginning

00:55:40.970 --> 00:55:43.830
of that adaptive process that
we've been talking about.

00:55:43.830 --> 00:55:46.350
Next.

00:55:46.350 --> 00:55:49.910
The design I don't need to
go into in great detail.

00:55:49.910 --> 00:55:53.180
The most important thing about
this slide is that I hope,

00:55:53.180 --> 00:55:55.940
and it's not because it's
out of focus, but because

00:55:55.940 --> 00:55:59.930
of design intent, you
can't see the edges

00:55:59.930 --> 00:56:04.470
of where the site begins or
the Olympic site and the rest.

00:56:04.470 --> 00:56:07.430
It sort of looks like
the rest of messy London.

00:56:07.430 --> 00:56:09.680
Next.

00:56:09.680 --> 00:56:13.470
And significantly,
the way in which

00:56:13.470 --> 00:56:17.490
the planning was conceived was
not to do it all in one go,

00:56:17.490 --> 00:56:20.790
because that is unrealistic,
not to start at one end

00:56:20.790 --> 00:56:23.550
and go down to the
bottom, not to start

00:56:23.550 --> 00:56:26.280
where the value is near
the railway stations

00:56:26.280 --> 00:56:27.820
and then build out.

00:56:27.820 --> 00:56:31.530
But to actually do it in a
piecemeal way, which reflects,

00:56:31.530 --> 00:56:33.870
again, the reality,
as Edgar called it,

00:56:33.870 --> 00:56:35.730
of the processes of city change.

00:56:35.730 --> 00:56:38.220
Next.

00:56:38.220 --> 00:56:40.230
This is how many
parts of London have

00:56:40.230 --> 00:56:42.000
grown for the last 200 years.

00:56:42.000 --> 00:56:44.340
Next.

00:56:44.340 --> 00:56:47.240
This is what the athletes'
village was like.

00:56:47.240 --> 00:56:49.500
Sorry, this is what was
the athletes' village

00:56:49.500 --> 00:56:52.950
and the picture taken
yesterday in what

00:56:52.950 --> 00:56:57.370
is part of the residential
community, which is roughly 50%

00:56:57.370 --> 00:57:01.500
affordable and 50% market
rental, known as the East

00:57:01.500 --> 00:57:02.190
Village.

00:57:02.190 --> 00:57:04.810
Next.

00:57:04.810 --> 00:57:05.620
There are schools.

00:57:05.620 --> 00:57:07.630
There are institutions
at the heart of it

00:57:07.630 --> 00:57:10.240
which serve not just the
new residents, but those

00:57:10.240 --> 00:57:11.270
in the surroundings.

00:57:11.270 --> 00:57:13.620
Next.

00:57:13.620 --> 00:57:19.470
There are 6,000 jobs created in
what used to be the [INAUDIBLE]

00:57:19.470 --> 00:57:20.970
great media hall.

00:57:20.970 --> 00:57:23.160
Next.

00:57:23.160 --> 00:57:26.640
Even the great swimming pool
designed by the late great Zaha

00:57:26.640 --> 00:57:32.380
Hadid, next, which
was symbolic and had

00:57:32.380 --> 00:57:35.500
17,000 seats during the games--

00:57:35.500 --> 00:57:38.954
next-- is now where,
for $5, anyone

00:57:38.954 --> 00:57:40.870
who lives in the
neighborhood can actually use

00:57:40.870 --> 00:57:43.360
as a literally community pool.

00:57:43.360 --> 00:57:45.360
Next.

00:57:45.360 --> 00:57:48.570
The notion of actually creating
a park at the middle of it

00:57:48.570 --> 00:57:50.700
has actually become
a resource, not just

00:57:50.700 --> 00:57:53.190
for those who live there,
because you don't know

00:57:53.190 --> 00:57:55.770
where the edge is, but for
the much wider surrounding

00:57:55.770 --> 00:57:56.310
community.

00:57:56.310 --> 00:57:58.670
Next.

00:57:58.670 --> 00:58:00.170
But things change.

00:58:00.170 --> 00:58:01.770
And Eve has raised this.

00:58:01.770 --> 00:58:05.630
The ability to adapt,
to be resilient

00:58:05.630 --> 00:58:07.860
is absolutely central.

00:58:07.860 --> 00:58:13.380
What you see here is the
canal on the right-hand side,

00:58:13.380 --> 00:58:17.580
the swimming complex, and
then a sort of large park

00:58:17.580 --> 00:58:20.340
area with water on both sides.

00:58:20.340 --> 00:58:23.970
No one really knew what
to do with this area.

00:58:23.970 --> 00:58:26.400
And actually what has happened
over the last three or four

00:58:26.400 --> 00:58:30.270
years, is that as the area,
the whole area of Stratford,

00:58:30.270 --> 00:58:33.840
has become more central
in the mind of Londoners

00:58:33.840 --> 00:58:37.650
and investors, next, a whole
series of organizations

00:58:37.650 --> 00:58:40.500
who would have never
touched this part of London,

00:58:40.500 --> 00:58:43.490
because of its distance
and its deprivation--

00:58:43.490 --> 00:58:47.550
the Victorian Albert Museum,
the University of the Arts,

00:58:47.550 --> 00:58:50.850
University College London, and
in fact, even the Smithsonian--

00:58:50.850 --> 00:58:54.990
next, are now actually
building new premises

00:58:54.990 --> 00:58:59.220
which will be part of a new
cultural quarter in a part

00:58:59.220 --> 00:59:01.750
of London that had no culture.

00:59:01.750 --> 00:59:03.370
Next.

00:59:03.370 --> 00:59:06.280
The most important
point I'm making here

00:59:06.280 --> 00:59:09.940
is that not
everything that we see

00:59:09.940 --> 00:59:13.240
happening in this part
of London was actually

00:59:13.240 --> 00:59:15.370
planned or understood.

00:59:15.370 --> 00:59:18.250
This is why I would
repeat and endorse

00:59:18.250 --> 00:59:21.190
the notion of not
anticipating outcomes,

00:59:21.190 --> 00:59:25.220
but to just provide a framework
which can adapt to them.

00:59:25.220 --> 00:59:26.670
Next.

00:59:26.670 --> 00:59:29.610
Let's look, very briefly,
in the last four minutes

00:59:29.610 --> 00:59:34.020
of my talk at the opposite
end of the scale in terms

00:59:34.020 --> 00:59:35.270
of investment.

00:59:35.270 --> 00:59:38.220
But perhaps similar
conclusions as to what

00:59:38.220 --> 00:59:42.600
might work or not work in
providing this wiggle room,

00:59:42.600 --> 00:59:44.970
in dealing with a
fragile urban fabric,

00:59:44.970 --> 00:59:47.220
particularly in
areas of deprivation.

00:59:47.220 --> 00:59:48.830
Next.

00:59:48.830 --> 00:59:51.770
In an area which has two of
the best connected railway

00:59:51.770 --> 00:59:53.960
stations, certainly
in England, if not

00:59:53.960 --> 00:59:56.270
in Europe, King's
Cross on the right

00:59:56.270 --> 01:00:00.110
and St. Pancras on the
left, is another gash,

01:00:00.110 --> 01:00:02.570
another gaping hole
of railway goods yard.

01:00:02.570 --> 01:00:06.200
Think of Hudson Yards in
New York as the equivalent.

01:00:06.200 --> 01:00:08.900
And keep that image of
Hudson Yards in your mind

01:00:08.900 --> 01:00:12.680
for a moment, all of you who
know what is being built there.

01:00:12.680 --> 01:00:17.150
This was an image
only in the year 2000.

01:00:17.150 --> 01:00:18.880
Next.

01:00:18.880 --> 01:00:21.430
This is an image of what's
actually going to be built,

01:00:21.430 --> 01:00:24.490
and much of it is actually
more or less realized,

01:00:24.490 --> 01:00:27.970
with homes, jobs, and
other facilities which

01:00:27.970 --> 01:00:28.990
I'm going to talk about.

01:00:28.990 --> 01:00:30.670
Next.

01:00:30.670 --> 01:00:32.590
It's a project
which has benefited

01:00:32.590 --> 01:00:36.490
from massive public transport
investment, that is true.

01:00:36.490 --> 01:00:38.500
But the 4 billion
dollars comes from

01:00:38.500 --> 01:00:43.510
Australian and Canadian pension
funds behind a front line

01:00:43.510 --> 01:00:44.680
developer.

01:00:44.680 --> 01:00:49.150
I think we need to reflect how
those sorts of actors, as you

01:00:49.150 --> 01:00:51.880
called it, Eve, can
actually benefit

01:00:51.880 --> 01:00:54.700
the structure of the city
rather than necessarily create

01:00:54.700 --> 01:00:55.870
yet another ghetto.

01:00:55.870 --> 01:00:57.780
Next.

01:00:57.780 --> 01:01:00.510
The way this part of
London was planned

01:01:00.510 --> 01:01:05.880
was to pick up the fine mix that
you see in surrounding areas.

01:01:05.880 --> 01:01:08.320
Next.

01:01:08.320 --> 01:01:11.140
The idea was, yes, it's private.

01:01:11.140 --> 01:01:15.100
But make it as connected
and as public as possible.

01:01:15.100 --> 01:01:17.110
Work on the streets
and the integration

01:01:17.110 --> 01:01:18.640
that we've heard of before.

01:01:18.640 --> 01:01:20.230
Next.

01:01:20.230 --> 01:01:23.230
Three diagrams to show
you what was important--

01:01:23.230 --> 01:01:26.880
take every possible connection,
every possible street

01:01:26.880 --> 01:01:29.620
that comes into the
site, and extend it

01:01:29.620 --> 01:01:30.940
into the neighborhood.

01:01:30.940 --> 01:01:32.800
That's a very strong
starting point

01:01:32.800 --> 01:01:34.750
for creating a
flexible framework.

01:01:34.750 --> 01:01:37.200
Next.

01:01:37.200 --> 01:01:39.660
Put on the ground
floor the mix of

01:01:39.660 --> 01:01:41.560
uses that you find
elsewhere in London,

01:01:41.560 --> 01:01:44.372
and don't just concentrate
them at the valuable end.

01:01:44.372 --> 01:01:46.080
What you see here in
the different colors

01:01:46.080 --> 01:01:48.600
are everything from
museum, housing,

01:01:48.600 --> 01:01:50.970
to places for work,
which were not expected

01:01:50.970 --> 01:01:52.860
in this part of London.

01:01:52.860 --> 01:01:54.890
Next.

01:01:54.890 --> 01:01:58.800
And the public
space, which you see

01:01:58.800 --> 01:02:00.870
colored in brown
effectively here,

01:02:00.870 --> 01:02:02.760
is the one cohesive
element which

01:02:02.760 --> 01:02:04.860
was fixed a few years ago.

01:02:04.860 --> 01:02:07.380
The uses of most of
the building have come

01:02:07.380 --> 01:02:11.220
in as the project has evolved.

01:02:11.220 --> 01:02:13.570
Next.

01:02:13.570 --> 01:02:15.700
Public space is
one example here.

01:02:15.700 --> 01:02:17.620
The buildings around
them, some are

01:02:17.620 --> 01:02:19.870
very good, some
are mediocre, seem

01:02:19.870 --> 01:02:22.450
to work well for the grain
of this part of London.

01:02:22.450 --> 01:02:24.250
Next.

01:02:24.250 --> 01:02:27.010
But most importantly,
no one knew

01:02:27.010 --> 01:02:29.770
what to do with that fantastic
building in the background

01:02:29.770 --> 01:02:32.320
called the Granary Building.

01:02:32.320 --> 01:02:37.130
And the University of the
Arts, next, moved into there,

01:02:37.130 --> 01:02:38.870
bringing-- next--

01:02:38.870 --> 01:02:41.960
5,000 students,
creative arts students,

01:02:41.960 --> 01:02:44.450
who make things, who are
there until three or four

01:02:44.450 --> 01:02:48.380
or five o'clock in the morning,
moved in as the first tenants,

01:02:48.380 --> 01:02:50.660
with I'm sure, some
very, very good deal

01:02:50.660 --> 01:02:54.210
when it came to the rent.

01:02:54.210 --> 01:02:57.210
But the point is that there
was a flexible enough structure

01:02:57.210 --> 01:02:58.170
to allow that.

01:02:58.170 --> 01:03:00.545
Next.

01:03:00.545 --> 01:03:02.110
Next.

01:03:02.110 --> 01:03:05.890
As a result of that, Google
decided to move all--

01:03:05.890 --> 01:03:10.120
all its European headquarters
into the site right next door.

01:03:10.120 --> 01:03:11.920
You could say
inspired by the fact

01:03:11.920 --> 01:03:14.320
that there are students
and creative types

01:03:14.320 --> 01:03:17.560
in the neighborhood, bringing,
in the next few years,

01:03:17.560 --> 01:03:19.990
8,000 employees to this
area that you really

01:03:19.990 --> 01:03:22.960
wouldn't have thought
would have attracted them.

01:03:22.960 --> 01:03:25.270
The design that you see
there is now being changed,

01:03:25.270 --> 01:03:30.160
next, a little
bit, unfortunately,

01:03:30.160 --> 01:03:34.579
inspired by Californian
notions of campus architecture.

01:03:34.579 --> 01:03:37.120
We're going to see what it looks
like in the next few months.

01:03:37.120 --> 01:03:38.380
Next.

01:03:38.380 --> 01:03:41.440
But interestingly,
this has also meant

01:03:41.440 --> 01:03:44.980
that Europe's largest medical
research facility has suddenly

01:03:44.980 --> 01:03:48.840
found its location there
next to the British Library.

01:03:48.840 --> 01:03:51.010
Next.

01:03:51.010 --> 01:03:55.480
Basically, I want to conclude by
saying that this project, which

01:03:55.480 --> 01:03:58.810
didn't have a name except
that it was a development,

01:03:58.810 --> 01:04:01.300
is now seen as London's
knowledge quarter.

01:04:01.300 --> 01:04:03.510
I know it's another brand.

01:04:03.510 --> 01:04:04.870
It's another name.

01:04:04.870 --> 01:04:06.715
But behind that,
as I said, there

01:04:06.715 --> 01:04:10.810
are 13,000 homes, of
which 50% are affordable,

01:04:10.810 --> 01:04:13.120
right in the middle
of London, where

01:04:13.120 --> 01:04:14.920
there is better access
to jobs than you

01:04:14.920 --> 01:04:16.240
could have anywhere else.

01:04:16.240 --> 01:04:19.060
Next.

01:04:19.060 --> 01:04:23.020
I showed you this image right
at the beginning, of Camden.

01:04:23.020 --> 01:04:25.930
It's a city which
has not been designed

01:04:25.930 --> 01:04:29.860
top down like Barcelona,
perhaps not even

01:04:29.860 --> 01:04:31.210
like the Manhattan grid.

01:04:31.210 --> 01:04:33.010
But it has similar
characteristics

01:04:33.010 --> 01:04:35.170
of adaptability.

01:04:35.170 --> 01:04:37.410
The point is, and this is
where I want to conclude,

01:04:37.410 --> 01:04:43.180
Eve, is that these adaptions
can be very fragile.

01:04:43.180 --> 01:04:45.960
You can take exactly the sort
of sites I've been talking about

01:04:45.960 --> 01:04:47.910
and turn them into fortresses.

01:04:47.910 --> 01:04:50.490
That's what's happening to
most of the new developments

01:04:50.490 --> 01:04:51.960
in the African city.

01:04:51.960 --> 01:04:54.990
That's what Edgar has
actually described to us.

01:04:54.990 --> 01:05:00.300
And that's why there's such a
strong anti-planning approach

01:05:00.300 --> 01:05:02.309
in many of the words
and many of the concepts

01:05:02.309 --> 01:05:03.600
that you've been talking about.

01:05:03.600 --> 01:05:04.950
Next.

01:05:04.950 --> 01:05:08.640
I would argue-- next, please--

01:05:08.640 --> 01:05:12.180
I would argue that in the end,
this planning model of London

01:05:12.180 --> 01:05:17.550
has one, at least allows us to
accept that cities are fragile.

01:05:17.550 --> 01:05:20.430
But that you can be
agile within that

01:05:20.430 --> 01:05:24.150
and provide a sort of resilient
framework, whereby planning

01:05:24.150 --> 01:05:26.580
returns in the 21st
century as something which

01:05:26.580 --> 01:05:34.080
is positive and applies not just
to the unique and rich cultures

01:05:34.080 --> 01:05:36.900
that we happen to belong
to in the global north,

01:05:36.900 --> 01:05:40.470
but can be applied and
adapted as we saw in Medellin,

01:05:40.470 --> 01:05:42.570
and I think need to
happen in Africa,

01:05:42.570 --> 01:05:46.447
but we're a very, very
long way away from that.

01:05:46.447 --> 01:05:47.280
Thank you very much.

01:05:47.280 --> 01:05:56.438
[APPLAUSE]

01:05:56.438 --> 01:05:57.620
- Thank you, Ricky.

01:05:57.620 --> 01:05:59.460
Can you hear me?

01:05:59.460 --> 01:06:03.040
- I can hear you, and I
think, I might even see you,

01:06:03.040 --> 01:06:04.740
or you might even
see me, I don't know.

01:06:09.222 --> 01:06:09.722
- Hi.

01:06:13.658 --> 01:06:15.890
This was wonderful.

01:06:15.890 --> 01:06:20.210
Three really fascinating
presentations.

01:06:20.210 --> 01:06:25.610
And each one actually very
different in terms of context

01:06:25.610 --> 01:06:31.700
obviously, also in terms of
scales and in terms of actors.

01:06:31.700 --> 01:06:33.920
And yet there are
common themes that

01:06:33.920 --> 01:06:38.240
run through them that I would
like to pick up and talk about.

01:06:38.240 --> 01:06:43.550
Edgar, I think just in terms of
taking the scaler issue here,

01:06:43.550 --> 01:06:45.830
that you're looking--

01:06:45.830 --> 01:06:51.170
what we're getting here is
the systemic scale and sort

01:06:51.170 --> 01:06:56.450
of what the larger
systems that actually

01:06:56.450 --> 01:07:00.170
structure society, that
include structuring

01:07:00.170 --> 01:07:02.880
the urban environment.

01:07:02.880 --> 01:07:05.390
And I think that one other
thing I wanted to say in here

01:07:05.390 --> 01:07:09.830
is that there also seems
to be one other theme that

01:07:09.830 --> 01:07:12.770
is emerging in all
of these three--

01:07:12.770 --> 01:07:15.170
or emerged in all of
these three talks,

01:07:15.170 --> 01:07:20.460
and that is what we can learn
from the informal, actually,

01:07:20.460 --> 01:07:22.250
and how we can learn from it.

01:07:22.250 --> 01:07:25.340
And one of the things I thought
that was very interesting

01:07:25.340 --> 01:07:32.060
about Edgar's presentation
was that, as he put it,

01:07:32.060 --> 01:07:35.990
the informal and the unplanned
processes and practices

01:07:35.990 --> 01:07:40.960
are constitutive in
both senses of the word,

01:07:40.960 --> 01:07:42.800
in meaning that
they're composed of

01:07:42.800 --> 01:07:46.940
and they also have the power
to give organized existence

01:07:46.940 --> 01:07:50.300
to something, that they
are in constitutive

01:07:50.300 --> 01:07:56.570
of human settlements, but also
of broader economic activity.

01:07:56.570 --> 01:07:58.910
And that that is,
as I understand

01:07:58.910 --> 01:08:01.550
it, a very important
thing if one

01:08:01.550 --> 01:08:04.970
is going to think about
intervening in the city,

01:08:04.970 --> 01:08:09.890
that it is an environment
that incorporates place making

01:08:09.890 --> 01:08:11.570
and work.

01:08:11.570 --> 01:08:17.899
And that the planning
potential of informal practices

01:08:17.899 --> 01:08:20.569
is this creation of employment.

01:08:20.569 --> 01:08:24.649
And the issue, it seems to me
that you were talking about,

01:08:24.649 --> 01:08:26.479
is the scaling up.

01:08:26.479 --> 01:08:30.979
How does one scale that up
from this sort of small scale

01:08:30.979 --> 01:08:35.689
interventions to
institutionalize

01:08:35.689 --> 01:08:38.180
these processes and
these relationships

01:08:38.180 --> 01:08:40.960
while still retaining
their flexibility.

01:08:40.960 --> 01:08:45.830
And Ana, the scale of your
project was much smaller,

01:08:45.830 --> 01:08:47.899
and actually-- but
what's so interesting

01:08:47.899 --> 01:08:51.200
about it is that the
same issues pertain

01:08:51.200 --> 01:08:53.270
at these different
scalar levels.

01:08:53.270 --> 01:08:57.410
So this is about social housing
in the city and the region,

01:08:57.410 --> 01:09:03.770
public and private projects
that open up a relationship

01:09:03.770 --> 01:09:05.600
or that have an
open relationship

01:09:05.600 --> 01:09:07.850
between the planned
and the unplanned,

01:09:07.850 --> 01:09:11.479
and particularly, you identified
interstitial spaces, these sort

01:09:11.479 --> 01:09:14.240
of mediating
spaces, thresholds I

01:09:14.240 --> 01:09:19.430
think you called them, where the
public and the private overlap.

01:09:19.430 --> 01:09:26.029
That provide spaces of
opportunity, that these are,

01:09:26.029 --> 01:09:28.250
and if we're thinking
now in planning terms--

01:09:28.250 --> 01:09:31.720
that planning is about the
public and the private--

01:09:31.720 --> 01:09:36.050
that it's these spaces
where these things become

01:09:36.050 --> 01:09:39.890
blurred that some
form of communal space

01:09:39.890 --> 01:09:41.660
has the potential to develop.

01:09:41.660 --> 01:09:49.340
And Ricky, fascinating projects,
publicly and privately funded.

01:09:49.340 --> 01:09:52.040
I think that your model
of fragility, agility,

01:09:52.040 --> 01:09:56.720
and resilience is
something that applies

01:09:56.720 --> 01:09:58.860
to all of these projects.

01:09:58.860 --> 01:10:03.220
And I think that
one of the things

01:10:03.220 --> 01:10:06.310
that I found interesting
in some of the terminology

01:10:06.310 --> 01:10:09.720
that you used, that
flexible spatial frameworks,

01:10:09.720 --> 01:10:13.630
and I think you used
that term, allows

01:10:13.630 --> 01:10:17.680
them to be shaped and
adapted and reappropriated

01:10:17.680 --> 01:10:20.860
through relatively
informal processes.

01:10:20.860 --> 01:10:26.440
And so what's happening here
is that formal and informal

01:10:26.440 --> 01:10:28.360
are becoming very relative.

01:10:28.360 --> 01:10:30.460
And so that the
boundaries between them

01:10:30.460 --> 01:10:34.120
are actually very fluid.

01:10:34.120 --> 01:10:38.290
And I think that there's also
a common vocabulary here,

01:10:38.290 --> 01:10:42.100
that the techniques and
processes are of appropriation.

01:10:42.100 --> 01:10:44.530
These are words that
everybody used, I think--

01:10:44.530 --> 01:10:50.740
adaptation, flexibility,
agility, resilience, hybridity.

01:10:50.740 --> 01:10:52.665
And there are a couple
of things that I

01:10:52.665 --> 01:10:54.040
think are interesting
out of that

01:10:54.040 --> 01:10:57.220
that I'd like to pose as
a question or something

01:10:57.220 --> 01:10:58.670
to talk about here.

01:10:58.670 --> 01:11:00.670
And that is this--

01:11:00.670 --> 01:11:02.410
fundamentally, what
we've been looking at

01:11:02.410 --> 01:11:05.290
is this relationship between
the planned and the unplanned.

01:11:05.290 --> 01:11:07.690
And while these
informal processes

01:11:07.690 --> 01:11:10.750
have tremendous
potential, everyone

01:11:10.750 --> 01:11:13.690
has mentioned the
importance of having a plan,

01:11:13.690 --> 01:11:15.200
that you need to have a plan.

01:11:15.200 --> 01:11:16.900
You need to have a
plan in the sense

01:11:16.900 --> 01:11:20.220
that you need to have a concept
of what you're trying to do,

01:11:20.220 --> 01:11:22.910
of what your objective is.

01:11:22.910 --> 01:11:28.900
And there has to be some
kind of agenda there.

01:11:28.900 --> 01:11:34.090
And so I wanted to throw
that out and see if you

01:11:34.090 --> 01:11:35.994
wanted to comment on that.

01:11:35.994 --> 01:11:37.882
- You want to start?

01:11:37.882 --> 01:11:40.250
- You can start.

01:11:40.250 --> 01:11:43.900
- Well, Eve, I think it's
important to understand, well,

01:11:43.900 --> 01:11:48.860
as I see it, that plan, the
concept of having a plan,

01:11:48.860 --> 01:11:54.700
is also a concept of defining a
physical definition of a space.

01:11:54.700 --> 01:11:57.110
And that's how I understand it.

01:11:57.110 --> 01:12:00.550
And the unplanned for
me is the people who

01:12:00.550 --> 01:12:03.170
come inside and interaction.

01:12:03.170 --> 01:12:07.030
So that's how I understand
planned and unplanned.

01:12:07.030 --> 01:12:09.280
Because you have a
definition of how do

01:12:09.280 --> 01:12:14.870
you want uses, spaces,
whatever you want to call it.

01:12:14.870 --> 01:12:17.650
But it is important to
understand that people come in.

01:12:17.650 --> 01:12:21.310
And it is the interaction
of that planned idea,

01:12:21.310 --> 01:12:25.780
how people are able to
develop their rituals,

01:12:25.780 --> 01:12:27.130
their understanding.

01:12:27.130 --> 01:12:30.550
And as Richard or
Ricky was saying,

01:12:30.550 --> 01:12:33.520
it allows that this
framework of the planned

01:12:33.520 --> 01:12:36.670
has to allow this
unplanned of the social.

01:12:36.670 --> 01:12:40.730
So I understand it as a
hardware and a software.

01:12:40.730 --> 01:12:43.030
And they do have to come
together all the time.

01:12:43.030 --> 01:12:48.400
You cannot think of them as
separate elements definitely.

01:12:48.400 --> 01:12:51.170
I don't know if that helps.

01:12:51.170 --> 01:12:53.320
- So slightly, yeah--

01:12:57.390 --> 01:13:00.790
so I guess the
idea of the plan--

01:13:00.790 --> 01:13:04.827
and as I suggested, to connect
it to the notion of narrative,

01:13:04.827 --> 01:13:06.910
and maybe that also will
see a useful connect back

01:13:06.910 --> 01:13:08.830
to the broader
thematic of why it

01:13:08.830 --> 01:13:10.390
is helpful to have
the humanities

01:13:10.390 --> 01:13:13.690
and the social sciences talk--

01:13:13.690 --> 01:13:18.010
is that, of course, the plan
goes to the heart of knowledge

01:13:18.010 --> 01:13:20.110
and control, right?

01:13:20.110 --> 01:13:23.860
And so in a lot of the
context that I'm interested in

01:13:23.860 --> 01:13:27.550
and that I work on,
it is the absence

01:13:27.550 --> 01:13:30.220
of the circulation of
knowledge or the deployment

01:13:30.220 --> 01:13:32.140
of certain kinds
of knowledges that

01:13:32.140 --> 01:13:38.830
allows a very, very small
elite to extract rents and make

01:13:38.830 --> 01:13:44.740
crazy profits and
essentially render

01:13:44.740 --> 01:13:48.100
the very same plan redundant.

01:13:48.100 --> 01:13:50.909
So there's a
politics of knowledge

01:13:50.909 --> 01:13:52.200
that I think is very important.

01:13:52.200 --> 01:13:55.690
So I'm very attracted to the
idea of the plan in that it

01:13:55.690 --> 01:14:00.820
allows us to bring transparency
to a set of processes

01:14:00.820 --> 01:14:04.020
that unfold that structures
the deployment of capital.

01:14:04.020 --> 01:14:06.910
And I mean capital
in the broad sense,

01:14:06.910 --> 01:14:09.100
both the meager
savings of the street

01:14:09.100 --> 01:14:15.700
trader and the
strategic opportunity

01:14:15.700 --> 01:14:19.300
that the pension
fund has spotted

01:14:19.300 --> 01:14:22.400
in whatever new development
is taking place.

01:14:22.400 --> 01:14:25.900
And so I think that
it is important,

01:14:25.900 --> 01:14:29.210
if we continue to invoke
the idea of the plan,

01:14:29.210 --> 01:14:34.480
that it provides a rationale and
a democratic discipline for it

01:14:34.480 --> 01:14:36.460
to effect transparency,
which then

01:14:36.460 --> 01:14:40.120
enables a different kind of
conversation to take place.

01:14:40.120 --> 01:14:43.810
Secondly, because
of precisely the way

01:14:43.810 --> 01:14:47.860
in which the city is built and
reproduced by the sheer effort

01:14:47.860 --> 01:14:53.536
and sweat and aspirations
of its inhabitants,

01:14:53.536 --> 01:14:54.910
there's an
opportunity for people

01:14:54.910 --> 01:14:56.330
to tell their own stories.

01:14:56.330 --> 01:15:00.700
I was really drawn to
the beautiful drawings

01:15:00.700 --> 01:15:03.760
that you reflected of how people
imagined they could inhabit

01:15:03.760 --> 01:15:08.920
these spaces as a part of
the process of imagining

01:15:08.920 --> 01:15:12.340
how the design could get
that calibration right--

01:15:12.340 --> 01:15:14.830
between the
structuring framework

01:15:14.830 --> 01:15:19.990
and leaving enough space for a
culturally infused inhabitation

01:15:19.990 --> 01:15:22.580
to make home and to make place.

01:15:22.580 --> 01:15:25.050
So I think that
this idea that there

01:15:25.050 --> 01:15:28.520
are a multiplicity of
registers within which we plan,

01:15:28.520 --> 01:15:31.600
in which we build narrative,
and in which we can, indeed,

01:15:31.600 --> 01:15:36.130
contest certain god
given narratives of how

01:15:36.130 --> 01:15:38.860
the city should be built,
or where investments should

01:15:38.860 --> 01:15:42.250
go first, is as
urgent politically

01:15:42.250 --> 01:15:44.650
and economically as
it could ever be.

01:15:44.650 --> 01:15:46.240
And just the last
point I want to make

01:15:46.240 --> 01:15:49.780
is that one of the things
that I struggle with

01:15:49.780 --> 01:15:54.070
is this really difficult,
often unintended,

01:15:54.070 --> 01:15:58.990
confluence of interest
between the need for obscurity

01:15:58.990 --> 01:16:01.390
on the side of the
dealmakers, the big deal

01:16:01.390 --> 01:16:05.370
makers, and the
effect of a really

01:16:05.370 --> 01:16:10.030
staid, top down, inwardly
looking bureaucratic mentality

01:16:10.030 --> 01:16:14.470
that treats the plan
as an artifact that

01:16:14.470 --> 01:16:21.744
is the only guarantor of
public autonomy or authority.

01:16:21.744 --> 01:16:23.410
Even though it doesn't
get implemented--

01:16:23.410 --> 01:16:26.290
but the amount of effort
bureaucratic planners

01:16:26.290 --> 01:16:28.390
spend in many African
local authorities

01:16:28.390 --> 01:16:30.550
and so forth to
perfect the plan--

01:16:30.550 --> 01:16:32.570
they know it's not
going to be used.

01:16:32.570 --> 01:16:36.310
But it's kind of the only
vestige of an attachment

01:16:36.310 --> 01:16:38.890
to authority that they have--

01:16:38.890 --> 01:16:42.310
serves the dealmakers
very, very well, right?

01:16:42.310 --> 01:16:44.510
And so there's also
a need, I think,

01:16:44.510 --> 01:16:47.950
to kind of radicalize
the idea of the plan,

01:16:47.950 --> 01:16:53.170
so that we can render strange
these incredibly dysfunctional

01:16:53.170 --> 01:16:54.004
practices.

01:16:54.004 --> 01:16:54.920
I don't know if that--

01:16:54.920 --> 01:16:57.520
- But I think,
Edgar, that can only

01:16:57.520 --> 01:17:02.410
happen if the actors involved
in shaping those plans,

01:17:02.410 --> 01:17:07.570
in commissioning those plans,
in designing those plans,

01:17:07.570 --> 01:17:13.840
have in their mind set a
sort of interdisciplinarity

01:17:13.840 --> 01:17:16.390
already in their head.

01:17:16.390 --> 01:17:19.210
What I'm getting
at is most planning

01:17:19.210 --> 01:17:23.680
is in the hands of
professions which value

01:17:23.680 --> 01:17:27.950
technique over social value.

01:17:27.950 --> 01:17:30.050
And I guess I am
getting at engineers,

01:17:30.050 --> 01:17:37.130
planners, who work in silos,
do not attend conferences

01:17:37.130 --> 01:17:39.980
like this one, and
where you don't

01:17:39.980 --> 01:17:44.480
get architects and engineers
talking to policy makers

01:17:44.480 --> 01:17:49.520
and sociologists, shall we say.

01:17:49.520 --> 01:17:51.020
I think this is an
important point,

01:17:51.020 --> 01:17:55.170
because many plans, and
particularly in African

01:17:55.170 --> 01:17:59.550
cities, are predicated on things
like we must improve access

01:17:59.550 --> 01:18:05.010
to mobility or
transport, full stop.

01:18:05.010 --> 01:18:09.420
It's a virtue and
an end in itself.

01:18:09.420 --> 01:18:14.360
If you look at the London plan
that I showed you very briefly,

01:18:14.360 --> 01:18:16.290
and if you remember
the inequality,

01:18:16.290 --> 01:18:18.960
the deprivation
map, the London plan

01:18:18.960 --> 01:18:23.140
can be summarized
in one sentence--

01:18:23.140 --> 01:18:27.460
To take the red areas,
the deprived areas,

01:18:27.460 --> 01:18:31.150
and redistribute them
across the city and not

01:18:31.150 --> 01:18:33.250
have an area of concentration.

01:18:33.250 --> 01:18:40.090
Therefore all the technical
investments, transport,

01:18:40.090 --> 01:18:44.620
broadband, better schools,
universities, education,

01:18:44.620 --> 01:18:47.320
are deployed as part
of that project.

01:18:47.320 --> 01:18:48.970
And I think that
that is something

01:18:48.970 --> 01:18:52.150
that would be interesting
to perhaps speculate on,

01:18:52.150 --> 01:18:56.320
whether that's
possible outside--

01:18:56.320 --> 01:19:02.080
let's call it some mature,
elite government, examples

01:19:02.080 --> 01:19:04.340
like the ones I've
been talking about.

01:19:04.340 --> 01:19:08.620
But then I want to throw in
perhaps a slight critique

01:19:08.620 --> 01:19:16.870
of democratic processes
that we have inherited.

01:19:16.870 --> 01:19:21.070
The UK has had a planning
process for the last 100

01:19:21.070 --> 01:19:22.820
plus years.

01:19:22.820 --> 01:19:24.680
The result of that
is that the voice

01:19:24.680 --> 01:19:28.970
of people living at the borough
level, the local authority

01:19:28.970 --> 01:19:34.130
level, is dominant when it comes
to giving planning permission.

01:19:34.130 --> 01:19:37.550
It's not community voiced,
but it's slightly above that.

01:19:37.550 --> 01:19:42.020
It's at the unit of
two, 300,000 people.

01:19:42.020 --> 01:19:45.320
Both the Olympic site
and the King's Cross site

01:19:45.320 --> 01:19:49.180
cut across different
political boundaries.

01:19:49.180 --> 01:19:52.180
So you have different zones with
different political allegiances

01:19:52.180 --> 01:19:54.400
and different
leaders and all that.

01:19:54.400 --> 01:19:59.590
The only way the Olympic
project happened,

01:19:59.590 --> 01:20:01.870
and only three or
four years have

01:20:01.870 --> 01:20:04.510
passed since we
had the games, was

01:20:04.510 --> 01:20:10.120
that the mayor put a red line
around the whole neighborhood

01:20:10.120 --> 01:20:13.990
and called it a Mayoral
Development Corporation,

01:20:13.990 --> 01:20:16.060
literally took the
power of decision

01:20:16.060 --> 01:20:18.730
making away from the boroughs.

01:20:18.730 --> 01:20:20.560
In the most bizarre
way, that meant

01:20:20.560 --> 01:20:23.080
that some of the bigger issues
of what London was about,

01:20:23.080 --> 01:20:26.290
as opposed to the
parochial issues of which

01:20:26.290 --> 01:20:29.800
small community, have prevailed.

01:20:29.800 --> 01:20:31.639
And we've ended up with
the sort of project

01:20:31.639 --> 01:20:32.680
that we're talking about.

01:20:32.680 --> 01:20:34.600
Now that is a
provocation, I realize,

01:20:34.600 --> 01:20:37.160
because it's really
going against the grain

01:20:37.160 --> 01:20:39.340
that small is beautiful
and every decision

01:20:39.340 --> 01:20:42.010
needs to be taken
at the lower level.

01:20:42.010 --> 01:20:45.430
I think you need some of
that big picture thinking,

01:20:45.430 --> 01:20:48.370
and big picture
institutional reframing

01:20:48.370 --> 01:20:49.900
to deliver some of these ideas.

01:20:52.410 --> 01:20:54.120
- I think that's
very interesting.

01:20:54.120 --> 01:20:57.450
Just a side note here,
one of the things

01:20:57.450 --> 01:20:59.160
that we've discovered
in the research

01:20:59.160 --> 01:21:03.330
that we were doing in the Mellon
Initiative on four cities,

01:21:03.330 --> 01:21:08.400
we've been looking at Berlin,
Boston, Mumbai, and Istanbul,

01:21:08.400 --> 01:21:11.250
is that, actually, one of the
interesting things about all

01:21:11.250 --> 01:21:16.080
these cities is that they
all seem to have a 2030 plan.

01:21:16.080 --> 01:21:18.900
They have some
aspirational plan,

01:21:18.900 --> 01:21:21.840
that this is what we
want our city to be.

01:21:21.840 --> 01:21:26.070
Berlin is an open city that
welcomes migrants, that has

01:21:26.070 --> 01:21:28.350
opportunities, that does this.

01:21:28.350 --> 01:21:31.720
The Boston plan has similar
kinds of aspirations.

01:21:31.720 --> 01:21:35.040
But that is, I
think, a little bit--

01:21:35.040 --> 01:21:38.010
of course, that's branding or
whatever you want to call it.

01:21:38.010 --> 01:21:39.680
But it's actually
more than that, too.

01:21:39.680 --> 01:21:44.670
It's a sense of our
larger sense of the city

01:21:44.670 --> 01:21:48.360
as being an aspirational
place, actually.

01:21:48.360 --> 01:21:52.080
That you can try,
you have goals,

01:21:52.080 --> 01:21:53.640
that there are common goals.

01:21:53.640 --> 01:21:56.340
And it's this notion of
the common good again.

01:21:56.340 --> 01:21:58.050
It's a romantic idea, perhaps.

01:21:58.050 --> 01:22:02.940
But I think that that's
part of this idea

01:22:02.940 --> 01:22:10.560
about the importance of the
plan as a narrative device,

01:22:10.560 --> 01:22:11.190
actually.

01:22:11.190 --> 01:22:14.250
That our city is about this.

01:22:14.250 --> 01:22:16.110
Our city is about
sustainability.

01:22:16.110 --> 01:22:18.970
Our city is about equity.

01:22:18.970 --> 01:22:24.468
Anyhow, I want to open it up
to the audience for questions.

01:22:24.468 --> 01:22:27.070
- Hello, I'm a Ben
[? Bolcher, ?] an alum

01:22:27.070 --> 01:22:28.945
of the GST here at Harvard.

01:22:28.945 --> 01:22:31.540
This is a question for Ricky.

01:22:31.540 --> 01:22:34.600
It seems that there is
a very uneven record

01:22:34.600 --> 01:22:38.860
of public investment in
Olympic projects historically,

01:22:38.860 --> 01:22:42.730
and at producing, and
that public value outcome.

01:22:42.730 --> 01:22:46.330
With regard to the
London project,

01:22:46.330 --> 01:22:48.850
is the kind of good
public outcome that

01:22:48.850 --> 01:22:51.640
is expected an
unintended consequence

01:22:51.640 --> 01:22:56.230
or are there structural lessons
to learn for future large scale

01:22:56.230 --> 01:22:59.600
projects of other Olympics
elsewhere from the London

01:22:59.600 --> 01:23:00.100
example?

01:23:02.860 --> 01:23:04.900
- Thank you for the question.

01:23:04.900 --> 01:23:08.230
Of course, I'm biased in
answering that question.

01:23:11.590 --> 01:23:15.790
There are very, very
different outcomes

01:23:15.790 --> 01:23:19.000
to different Olympic projects.

01:23:19.000 --> 01:23:22.180
And what we did
in London was very

01:23:22.180 --> 01:23:25.330
simply follow the ones that
worked and studied them

01:23:25.330 --> 01:23:25.990
very carefully.

01:23:25.990 --> 01:23:30.070
And Barcelona clearly, of
the 1992 games of Barcelona,

01:23:30.070 --> 01:23:32.170
is a very clear
model, which goes back

01:23:32.170 --> 01:23:34.450
to exactly what Eve was saying.

01:23:34.450 --> 01:23:37.630
They were not shy about
having a social program.

01:23:37.630 --> 01:23:40.480
And the Olympics was a way of
achieving that social program.

01:23:40.480 --> 01:23:46.840
So I think, in that sense, we
did very much copy that model.

01:23:46.840 --> 01:23:49.900
There were examples
that we could look at,

01:23:49.900 --> 01:23:53.170
some of them, for
example, Athens,

01:23:53.170 --> 01:23:57.130
which had been recently held,
whereby vast investment had

01:23:57.130 --> 01:24:01.540
been made without any notion of
how the different venues would

01:24:01.540 --> 01:24:05.050
actually fit within the social,
economic, and cultural fabric

01:24:05.050 --> 01:24:06.410
of the city.

01:24:06.410 --> 01:24:08.110
And I know this is
dangerous territory,

01:24:08.110 --> 01:24:11.110
but the Atlanta and Los
Angeles models of Olympics

01:24:11.110 --> 01:24:13.960
are not necessarily
the best examples

01:24:13.960 --> 01:24:18.430
of how to look at long
term sustainable commitment

01:24:18.430 --> 01:24:19.700
to the future of the city.

01:24:19.700 --> 01:24:22.840
If one thinks of what
happens in terms of riots

01:24:22.840 --> 01:24:25.210
and elsewhere in Los
Angeles not that many years

01:24:25.210 --> 01:24:27.250
after those Olympic games.

01:24:27.250 --> 01:24:34.630
I think in terms of using the
London Olympics to do what it's

01:24:34.630 --> 01:24:38.260
trying to do, we
can't claim in any way

01:24:38.260 --> 01:24:40.870
that it's just the
London Olympics project.

01:24:40.870 --> 01:24:45.280
It fits into a much deeper,
longer term thinking

01:24:45.280 --> 01:24:52.420
of how government can intervene
going back to Edgar's point

01:24:52.420 --> 01:24:57.630
to redistribute wealth and
actually create greater equity

01:24:57.630 --> 01:24:59.100
across the surface of the city.

01:24:59.100 --> 01:25:01.680
So this was an
example, and I'm told

01:25:01.680 --> 01:25:04.350
by a number of serious
economists that the London

01:25:04.350 --> 01:25:07.350
School of Economics
so it must be true,

01:25:07.350 --> 01:25:13.140
that we accelerated the
regeneration and possible

01:25:13.140 --> 01:25:17.070
equalization of London
by around 70 years

01:25:17.070 --> 01:25:18.654
as a result of this process.

01:25:18.654 --> 01:25:20.070
But it was going
to happen anyway.

01:25:25.501 --> 01:25:26.000
- Hello.

01:25:26.000 --> 01:25:27.230
My name is Dale Hepler.

01:25:27.230 --> 01:25:29.870
I'm an architect here in Boston.

01:25:29.870 --> 01:25:32.222
My question is for Edgar.

01:25:32.222 --> 01:25:35.570
You used a phrase a couple of
times that I found intriguing.

01:25:35.570 --> 01:25:39.470
You were saying
narrative-based planning.

01:25:39.470 --> 01:25:42.170
I was hoping you could
explain a little bit more

01:25:42.170 --> 01:25:45.410
how narrative
influences planning,

01:25:45.410 --> 01:25:50.000
or especially in the range
of talks we've heard today.

01:25:50.000 --> 01:25:53.050
- Yeah, so it actually connects
very directly to Eve's point.

01:25:53.050 --> 01:25:55.400
So I think that-- and
also some of the points

01:25:55.400 --> 01:25:56.930
Ricky has been making.

01:25:56.930 --> 01:25:59.360
So we've got to recognize
that there's, of course,

01:25:59.360 --> 01:26:01.250
different scales at play.

01:26:01.250 --> 01:26:06.830
And we need a different set
of practices and processes

01:26:06.830 --> 01:26:09.590
and sense and
institutional sensibilities

01:26:09.590 --> 01:26:11.280
at these different scales.

01:26:11.280 --> 01:26:13.790
So if we go back to the
earlier panels of today dealing

01:26:13.790 --> 01:26:18.470
with climate impacts, crisis of
water management and so forth,

01:26:18.470 --> 01:26:21.710
these require, by definition,
a metropolitan regional

01:26:21.710 --> 01:26:22.490
perspective.

01:26:22.490 --> 01:26:27.080
You can't resolve those
questions one block at a time.

01:26:27.080 --> 01:26:30.680
And it is impossible, because
of the sheer complexity

01:26:30.680 --> 01:26:34.160
and going back, I guess, to the
big data point this morning,

01:26:34.160 --> 01:26:38.750
to in a way have an
inclusive democratic process,

01:26:38.750 --> 01:26:42.260
to deliberate on those questions
at the scale of the city

01:26:42.260 --> 01:26:43.970
region.

01:26:43.970 --> 01:26:47.690
So the tendency towards
these 2030 plans,

01:26:47.690 --> 01:26:50.930
2040 plans and so
forth, is a reflection

01:26:50.930 --> 01:26:54.140
of trying to construct a
narrative that can deal

01:26:54.140 --> 01:26:56.150
with that regional complexity.

01:26:56.150 --> 01:26:59.180
And the key word that emerges
typically from those plans

01:26:59.180 --> 01:27:01.610
is this idea of
growth management.

01:27:01.610 --> 01:27:04.700
And in the last five years,
you combine growth management

01:27:04.700 --> 01:27:06.230
with resilience, right?

01:27:06.230 --> 01:27:09.560
And then your consultancy
practice will,

01:27:09.560 --> 01:27:11.510
you know, good business
for the next 20 years.

01:27:15.350 --> 01:27:17.870
So this is where the rub lies.

01:27:17.870 --> 01:27:20.630
That, of course, when you
talk about growth management

01:27:20.630 --> 01:27:24.710
or resilience,
immediately a whole suite

01:27:24.710 --> 01:27:28.490
of stabilized meanings
come to the fore

01:27:28.490 --> 01:27:31.830
that are mediated by
consultancy practices.

01:27:31.830 --> 01:27:35.270
And I think this is incredibly
dangerous, because people stop

01:27:35.270 --> 01:27:39.170
to think, they stop to
really work with the data,

01:27:39.170 --> 01:27:42.590
and they stop to
bring to forward

01:27:42.590 --> 01:27:46.820
the constitutive conflicts
and conflicts of interest,

01:27:46.820 --> 01:27:50.990
both generationally and at
the city-regional scale.

01:27:50.990 --> 01:27:53.150
Which is why the London
example is so interesting

01:27:53.150 --> 01:27:56.420
is precisely because it
takes a regional perspective

01:27:56.420 --> 01:27:59.750
and says that's the
zone of deep deprivation

01:27:59.750 --> 01:28:01.916
with cumulative disadvantage.

01:28:01.916 --> 01:28:03.290
And at the same
time, when you're

01:28:03.290 --> 01:28:06.530
going to pop $50
billion, you've got

01:28:06.530 --> 01:28:09.080
to think about three
generations into the future

01:28:09.080 --> 01:28:11.870
and who represents
their interests.

01:28:11.870 --> 01:28:14.630
So I think that, for me,
the narrative is then

01:28:14.630 --> 01:28:17.960
how do we foreground the
tradeoffs and the decisions

01:28:17.960 --> 01:28:20.300
and the assumptions
of that narrative?

01:28:20.300 --> 01:28:23.270
And for me, the planning
process could, potentially,

01:28:23.270 --> 01:28:26.960
if it is curated properly,
could service that

01:28:26.960 --> 01:28:30.230
and at least have an
informed public discourse.

01:28:30.230 --> 01:28:32.720
So because the issue is not
that that gives you the best

01:28:32.720 --> 01:28:35.930
outcome, but it creates
a democratic atmosphere

01:28:35.930 --> 01:28:39.860
within which a certain political
leadership is called for.

01:28:39.860 --> 01:28:43.310
And that's what we need is
the politicization of planning

01:28:43.310 --> 01:28:45.790
and that the right
kinds of pressure points

01:28:45.790 --> 01:28:48.480
are applied by a
plurality of interests.

01:28:48.480 --> 01:28:52.070
And at the same time, at
the local level, for me

01:28:52.070 --> 01:28:53.090
it's very clear.

01:28:53.090 --> 01:28:57.440
If I look at a crowd, or I look
at a slum in Cape Town or so,

01:28:57.440 --> 01:29:00.560
that people's kind of
social, reproductive needs

01:29:00.560 --> 01:29:02.975
are what all of us
aspire to and want--

01:29:02.975 --> 01:29:06.710
is our kids in a good
school, not being exposed

01:29:06.710 --> 01:29:12.500
to sexual predators, being able
to access good quality food,

01:29:12.500 --> 01:29:14.840
have energy security, et cetera.

01:29:14.840 --> 01:29:16.310
So this is not rocket science.

01:29:16.310 --> 01:29:17.840
We know this.

01:29:17.840 --> 01:29:21.980
But the point is that because
of this cumulative process

01:29:21.980 --> 01:29:24.710
of exclusion and
social injustice,

01:29:24.710 --> 01:29:27.170
it is very complex to
work out where do you

01:29:27.170 --> 01:29:31.270
get the resources to intervene
in a dense, if you will,

01:29:31.270 --> 01:29:33.550
milieu of compensation.

01:29:33.550 --> 01:29:35.350
Where people have
kind of improvised

01:29:35.350 --> 01:29:38.480
to do all kinds of things
to get by, but even that,

01:29:38.480 --> 01:29:42.140
at the intimate scale, are shot
through with power relations.

01:29:42.140 --> 01:29:46.880
So how do we build a way
of opening up those logics

01:29:46.880 --> 01:29:49.700
through the voice
and the practices

01:29:49.700 --> 01:29:52.730
and the experience of people
who live there, who constitute

01:29:52.730 --> 01:29:56.870
that reality, and animate that
in a pedagogic way for them

01:29:56.870 --> 01:30:00.770
to imagine other possibilities
and other ways of doing?

01:30:00.770 --> 01:30:03.590
And I think we're at a very
interesting cusp, where

01:30:03.590 --> 01:30:06.830
if you look at what's happening
in East Africa with micro-grids

01:30:06.830 --> 01:30:10.100
and energy systems that is
working off M-Pesa, which

01:30:10.100 --> 01:30:19.430
is a mobile phone, a dumb mobile
phone financial system that

01:30:19.430 --> 01:30:22.790
is enabling new
micro-grids to be operated

01:30:22.790 --> 01:30:26.260
by slum dwellers themselves.

01:30:26.260 --> 01:30:27.990
And that's one example.

01:30:27.990 --> 01:30:30.200
So the point is that
planning in that context

01:30:30.200 --> 01:30:35.260
is about making legible
a narrative people have

01:30:35.260 --> 01:30:36.570
of how they get by.

01:30:36.570 --> 01:30:39.300
But also, if one animated,
which is the planning

01:30:39.300 --> 01:30:43.830
part, in a creative way, one can
build new imaginations of what

01:30:43.830 --> 01:30:45.360
that neighborhood could become.

01:30:45.360 --> 01:30:48.570
And so narrative, I think,
works at different scales

01:30:48.570 --> 01:30:49.530
in different ways.

01:30:49.530 --> 01:30:52.590
But you need very different
pedagogic techniques

01:30:52.590 --> 01:30:56.090
to build that narrative
and to build it critically.

01:30:56.090 --> 01:30:58.740
- Thank you.

01:30:58.740 --> 01:31:01.170
- If resiliency also
means pulling back

01:31:01.170 --> 01:31:04.620
in the not so far future,
like Miami or Lagos,

01:31:04.620 --> 01:31:08.190
or for that matter, London,
as the seas get higher,

01:31:08.190 --> 01:31:09.660
you're going to lose some land.

01:31:09.660 --> 01:31:11.670
You may not have the
space or the infilling,

01:31:11.670 --> 01:31:13.690
like you just explained.

01:31:13.690 --> 01:31:16.140
You're going to have to
go somewhere or go up.

01:31:16.140 --> 01:31:17.580
What type of
planning is at least

01:31:17.580 --> 01:31:20.520
being conceptualized
to try to do--

01:31:20.520 --> 01:31:22.710
a Dutch solution only
buys you some time.

01:31:22.710 --> 01:31:26.790
If the seas keep
rising as projected,

01:31:26.790 --> 01:31:28.336
we have time to plan for that.

01:31:28.336 --> 01:31:30.210
But it still means you've
got to go somewhere

01:31:30.210 --> 01:31:32.670
with a lot of people
that have been displaced

01:31:32.670 --> 01:31:34.740
or a lot of facilities,
such as sewer plants

01:31:34.740 --> 01:31:36.323
or what have you,
that are going to be

01:31:36.323 --> 01:31:37.713
displaced by this activity.

01:31:40.431 --> 01:31:42.510
- I mean, Dilip
is in the audience

01:31:42.510 --> 01:31:48.310
so there's no way I'm responding
to that question, right?

01:31:48.310 --> 01:31:50.940
So I think that--
and Ricky will have

01:31:50.940 --> 01:31:54.630
things to say about this
because the LSE city center runs

01:31:54.630 --> 01:31:57.300
an expansive research
program in different cities

01:31:57.300 --> 01:32:01.050
on questions of climate
adaptation and resilience.

01:32:01.050 --> 01:32:03.840
But just to say very
briefly that, of course,

01:32:03.840 --> 01:32:08.520
there are the big events in
terms of the large climate

01:32:08.520 --> 01:32:10.017
impacts and the
form of sea level

01:32:10.017 --> 01:32:11.100
rise and the consequences.

01:32:11.100 --> 01:32:16.230
But, of course, a more critical
and important aspect of that

01:32:16.230 --> 01:32:18.990
is the immediate
climate variability,

01:32:18.990 --> 01:32:21.270
and the way in
which that impacts,

01:32:21.270 --> 01:32:23.546
in a highly disproportionate
way on the most

01:32:23.546 --> 01:32:25.920
vulnerable in the city, which,
of course, are the poorest

01:32:25.920 --> 01:32:28.200
people who live in
the most precarious

01:32:28.200 --> 01:32:30.490
environmentally sensitive areas.

01:32:30.490 --> 01:32:32.386
So I think it is very
important, and it's

01:32:32.386 --> 01:32:36.690
the only point I will make, that
we don't slip into a discourse

01:32:36.690 --> 01:32:39.340
that this is something that
allows for anticipatory

01:32:39.340 --> 01:32:40.710
planning over the long term.

01:32:43.600 --> 01:32:46.610
The devastation
is happening now.

01:32:46.610 --> 01:32:48.620
Ricky?

01:32:48.620 --> 01:32:50.420
- Well, I mean,
again, there are so

01:32:50.420 --> 01:32:54.080
many other people who know
more about this than I do,

01:32:54.080 --> 01:32:55.880
and probably in the room.

01:32:55.880 --> 01:32:58.400
And the difference between
mitigation and adaptation

01:32:58.400 --> 01:33:02.060
is central to this very
intelligent question.

01:33:02.060 --> 01:33:07.310
All I would say is
that controlling land,

01:33:07.310 --> 01:33:08.897
not just in terms
of speculation,

01:33:08.897 --> 01:33:10.730
which is what Eve had
said at the beginning,

01:33:10.730 --> 01:33:15.680
but in terms of where land
is most risky, stopping

01:33:15.680 --> 01:33:19.370
informal development happening
exactly in those areas

01:33:19.370 --> 01:33:21.830
which is most risky--

01:33:21.830 --> 01:33:25.940
think of Jakarta, think of
Lagos, think of elsewhere--

01:33:25.940 --> 01:33:30.260
requires a degree
of political control

01:33:30.260 --> 01:33:33.590
which unfortunately is missing
in many of these areas.

01:33:33.590 --> 01:33:36.290
Referring to the point that
Edgar has made about our work

01:33:36.290 --> 01:33:39.980
is certainly an intelligent
and well-planned form

01:33:39.980 --> 01:33:44.510
of high density development must
be the answer to this, because

01:33:44.510 --> 01:33:47.660
of the critical mass and
also the structural solidity.

01:33:47.660 --> 01:33:50.000
But also being pragmatic
and realistic about it.

01:33:50.000 --> 01:33:53.690
The best example I know
is the whole redevelopment

01:33:53.690 --> 01:33:58.610
of the waterfront area in
Hamburg called HafenCity,

01:33:58.610 --> 01:34:00.680
where basically it's
acknowledged that there

01:34:00.680 --> 01:34:07.220
will be a five meter devastating
flood at some point in time.

01:34:07.220 --> 01:34:08.780
And therefore the
city has actually

01:34:08.780 --> 01:34:11.810
been designed in such a way
that only garages, depots,

01:34:11.810 --> 01:34:18.080
and a degree of retail is in
that lower level, landscaping

01:34:18.080 --> 01:34:19.040
and much else.

01:34:19.040 --> 01:34:21.800
Actually, some of it
incredibly beautiful.

01:34:21.800 --> 01:34:25.610
But it doesn't stop the
city from actually expanding

01:34:25.610 --> 01:34:29.180
into the port area and making
it a very important addition

01:34:29.180 --> 01:34:29.690
to the city.

01:34:29.690 --> 01:34:34.910
But taking completely
in mind that you

01:34:34.910 --> 01:34:38.750
don't want to expose
people, and particularly

01:34:38.750 --> 01:34:43.100
those who are most at risk
as Edgar has described.

01:34:43.100 --> 01:34:45.930
In the case of
London, very simply,

01:34:45.930 --> 01:34:49.100
if you went a bit, two
miles further east of where

01:34:49.100 --> 01:34:52.670
the Olympics are, you would
actually be within a flood zone

01:34:52.670 --> 01:34:56.600
and different regulations apply
to how housing is actually

01:34:56.600 --> 01:35:00.160
built.

