01:35:45.120 --> 01:35:49.170
to work on the complex
phenomenon of urbanism.

01:35:49.170 --> 01:35:50.850
When we first
started this project,

01:35:50.850 --> 01:35:53.880
Eve drew my attention
to a small book

01:35:53.880 --> 01:35:57.440
written by the French Marxist
sociologist and philosopher

01:35:57.440 --> 01:35:59.160
Henri Lefebvre.

01:35:59.160 --> 01:36:01.800
His much better known work,
The Production of Space

01:36:01.800 --> 01:36:05.250
is one of my faves, but I
hadn't known about his shorter

01:36:05.250 --> 01:36:07.740
book, The Urban Revolution.

01:36:07.740 --> 01:36:10.620
And in that book which he
wrote nearly 50 years ago

01:36:10.620 --> 01:36:13.830
he made a distinction
between the urban phenomenon

01:36:13.830 --> 01:36:17.760
and the city that I think has
even greater resonance for us

01:36:17.760 --> 01:36:18.810
today.

01:36:18.810 --> 01:36:21.060
According to the
Lefebvre, the city

01:36:21.060 --> 01:36:23.610
is a term that
attempts to designate

01:36:23.610 --> 01:36:28.680
a clearly defined, definitive
object, a scientific object.

01:36:28.680 --> 01:36:32.040
Whereas the urban, he
says, is pure form--

01:36:32.040 --> 01:36:36.360
a place of encounter,
assembly and simultaneity.

01:36:36.360 --> 01:36:39.450
This form has no
content, but is a center

01:36:39.450 --> 01:36:41.640
of attraction and life.

01:36:41.640 --> 01:36:44.970
The urban is neither
an object, substance,

01:36:44.970 --> 01:36:47.550
nor a subject, consciousness.

01:36:47.550 --> 01:36:51.820
The urban phenomenon is
made manifest as movement.

01:36:51.820 --> 01:36:55.440
So that's Lefebvre, way
back, almost 50 years ago.

01:36:55.440 --> 01:36:59.130
I hope this conference has
helped us to think together

01:36:59.130 --> 01:37:02.400
about how to approach
this dynamic moving

01:37:02.400 --> 01:37:07.020
target of urbanism in the global
age, issues in which we all

01:37:07.020 --> 01:37:08.280
